<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIBA Agrees to Free Player Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MUNICH, December 2 (Xinhua) -- World basketball governing body
FIBA, which has previously restricted European club teams to two
non-European players, has agreed in principle to the free
movement of players worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement announced in Munich, Germany, on Wednesday
by FIBA, basketball players will be free to join any club team in
the world without restriction.
</P>
<P>
"What it means is a team like Real Madrid could field 10
Americans if they wanted,'' FIBA spokesman Florian Wanninger
said. "It puts us in line with the NBA, which has no limit of any
kind on foreign players."
</P>
<P>
Seventeen of FIBA's 20-member central board voted in favor of
the change, which could be in force next season. Details are
expected to be ironed out at a FIBA meeting in May in Barcelona,
Spain.
</P>
<P>
FIBA has also proposed the change to end the practice of
non-EU players seeking EU passports in order to be counted as a
national player instead of a foreigner.
</P>
<P>
The increasing practice has set off disputes between national
basketball federations.
</P>
<P>
At this year's World Championship in Athens, 2.12-meter Dragan
Tarlac, a Yugoslav with a Greek passport who plays with Greek
club Olympiakos, declined to play for Yugoslavia's national team
for fear of a legal battle.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
