<HEADLINE> African Coffee Producers Urged to Raise Domestic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Secretary of State for
Coffee Gilberto Buta Lutucuta Wednesday called upon the African
coffee producing countries to act immediately to increase their
domestic needs.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held in Luanda here, Lutucuta noted that
the supply of coffee is more than the demand in the international
market and the prices for coffee are dipping.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan coffee official pointed out that the domestic
demands in coffee producing countries are less than 10 percent of
their production.
</P>
<P>
The African coffee producing countries agreed late last month
that they should take steps immediately to raise their domestic
demands for coffee in a bid to change the unfavorable situation
on the world market, said Lutucuta.
</P>
<P>
He added that besides increasing the output of coffee, the
African producers should also improve the quality of the cocoa
beans they export.
</P>
<P>
From May to September this year, Lutucuta said, the coffee
prices had been on decrease in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Currently, one kilogram of Robusto coffee is sold at 1.6 U.S.
Dollars while the Arabica coffee sold at 3.2 Dollars per
kilogram, he added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, most of the cocoa bean exports have quality problems
and some even carry such viruses as trachiamicose, ochratoxine
and mofo.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state also disclosed that the output of
coffee for 1998/99 in Angola is expected to top 10,000 tons. But
he pointed out that Angola may harvest only 5,000 tons of coffee
due to domestic conflicts and the abnormal climate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
