<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Leather Exporters Urged to Meet World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Leather and Leather
Products Technology Institute of Ethiopia is urged Wednesday to
play an important role in assisting national efforts to bolster
the supply to the world market of leather and leather products.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, the call was made here
by an Ethiopian leather products exporter, Teshome Kebede, in an
interview with the national news agency.
</P>
<P>
Teshome said that Ethiopia has not been able to supply the
world market with leather and leather products in the required
quality and quantity.
</P>
<P>
"Although Ethiopia is rich in skin resources," Teshome said,
"lack of modern and well-equipped pickling and tanning factories
have thwarted efforts of the nation to be a leading competitor in
the international leather market."
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has the largest livestock population in Africa,
including 33 million head of cattle, 23 million sheep and 13
million goats.
</P>
<P>
The total world exports of hides and skins amounted to 4.59
billion U.S. Dollars in 1994, but Ethiopia's share remains small
at 57 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
A majority of hides and skins are wasted as a result of
quality loss due to obsolete equipment and unskilled practices.
</P>
<P>
Teshome said that two types of Ethiopian skins, Bati goat skin
and Selale sheep skin, are famous for their quality in the
international market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
