<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Will Eliminate Visa Need for Baltics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Germany and the Baltic states -
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania - will sign an accord this month,
canceling the Requirement for Baltic nationals to get travel
visas, a Bonn foreign ministry spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nationals from the three countries will no longer need a visa
to visit Germany from March 1, 1999 under an agreement which will
be signed December 16 in Berlin, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Baltic nationals will make free travel to much of Europe under
the Schengen Accord, because Germany has scrapped border controls
with nine of the European Union (EU)'s 15 member states.
</P>
<P>
The nine states, which are members of the Schengen bloc, are:
Austria, Belgium, France, Germany, Italy, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Portugal and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Greece is a Schengen member, too, but border controls have not
been lifted between Greece and other Schengen states. Denmark,
Finland and Sweden have joined the Schengen bloc but are not fully
integrated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
