<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Set Pollutant Limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) will set
for the first time air quality limit values for benzene and carbon
monoxide gases, according to an EU-proposed directive adopted
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The main goals of the directive are to protect the public from
health damage and enhance the life quality of the citizens in the
15 member states of the organization, especially in the crowded
towns and cities, said the EU commission, the executive body of EU.
</P>
<P>
The proposal set limit values for benzene at 5 micrograms per
cubic meter, which should be met on January 1, 2010, and limit
values for carbon monoxide at 10 micrograms per cubic meter, which
is to be met on January 1, 2005.
</P>
<P>
To achieve these targets, the commission said, emissions of
benzene, the first carcinogen subject to an air quality limit
value, must drop by nearly 70 percent in addition to reductions
already planned. The peak level of carbon monoxide must also drop
by up to a third.
</P>
<P>
The EU said the proposal is just part of an action program
launched within the framework of its Directive on Ambient Air
Quality Assessment and Management.
</P>
<P>
Proposals for tackling other pollutants including other
carcinogens will follow, said the European Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
