<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO to Elect Future Director-General by Mid-December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Members of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) will elect their future director-general by
mid-December at the latest, said WTO sources here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They failed to meet the previous deadline by the end of
November to form a consensus on choosing one of the four
candidates: Morocco's Hassan Abuyoub, Canada's Roy MacLaren, New
Zealand's Mike Moore and Thailand's Supachai Panitchpakdi.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero of Italy has
said that he will not run for the position again when his term
expires next April.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the consultations should aim to make
it possible for WTO members to elect the new chief by consensus.
The content of the consultations was to be secret, in particular
the positions and views expressed by the representatives of the
members.
</P>
<P>
A large majority of the members hold that recourse to a vote,
whether a straw ballot or a final election vote, must be ruled
out.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, two rounds of secret consultations have taken place.
The first round between late October and early November was
attended by 46 heads of delegations, representing more than 65 WTO
members. They discussed mainly the nature and modalities of the
selection process for the next director-general. But none of them
met with any of the four delegates during the first round.
</P>
<P>
At the second round on November 24-26, 70 heads of delegations,
representing 90 members, informed the meeting of their
authorities' appreciation of each one of the four candidates and
the reasons for their preferences.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that a certain number of the 132 delegations
have not yet been able to inform the WTO of their authorities'
position on the four candidates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
