<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French-British Summit to Focus on Cooperation in Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
and British Prime Minister Tony Blair will focus their talks on
bilateral cooperation in defense and security during their summit
to be held Thursday and Friday in Saint Malo, western France.
</P>
<P>
A French foreign ministry spokesman said on Wednesday that
Paris and London will start dialogue on defense cooperation and
thus contributing to building European capacities and means of
action in defense and security.
</P>
<P>
Britain changed its stand last month by agreeing to discuss
with France, Germany and some European countries the construction
of a European defense. But London insists that all military
operations by European countries should be conducted under the
auspices of the NATO.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that France wishes that European Union (EU)
assume control of political and strategical operations of a future
European defense force, including collaborations with the NATO.
</P>
<P>
France, Germany and Italy agree that the 28-member Western
European Union (WEU), which is the only European forum of defense,
should be integrated into the EU.
</P>
<P>
While agreeing to join the process of building a European
defense ``without being diverted by institutional obstacles,''
London says that the WEU should hand over its political role to
EU, and its military role to NATO.
</P>
<P>
British defense secretary George Robertson and foreign
secretary Robin Cook are meeting their French counterparts Alain
Richard and Hubert Vedrine in Paris to prepare for the summit.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to focus their talks on the future of the WEU
and increasing exchange of information between the two foreign
ministries and their missions around the world.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the British government said on Wednesday that
Britain and France will sign an agreement on cooperation in crisis
prevention operations such as that in former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
They will also agree to increase cooperation in Africa by
arranging joint visits by government ministers of the two
countries to African countries, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
France and Britain have military cooperation agreements in
army, navy and air force and nuclear fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
