<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Land Reform to Go Ahead: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will
go ahead with its program to compulsorily acquire mostly
white-owned commercial farms for resettling the landless black
majority, a Zimbabwean minister said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Land Acquisition Committee Joseph Msika, who
is also chairman of the ruling ZANU (PF) party and Minister
without Portfolio, delivered a keynote address at a Zimbabwean
Farmers Union workshop here to discuss the land issue.
</P>
<P>
Msika told the workshop that the majority of Zimbabweans still
lived in marginal rural land with infertile soil and unreliable
rainfall.
</P>
<P>
At independence from Britain in 1980, he said, 6,000 farmers,
mainly white, owned 45 percent of the most fertile land while
communal areas with 700,000 farming households occupied less than
50 percent of the agricultural land.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question from a workshop participant, Msika
ruled out taxing people to raise money for acquiring farms for
resettlement.
</P>
<P>
He said that Zimbabweans would not accept to be taxed to raise
money for buying the more than 1,400 farms designated for
acquisition by the government last November because the land was
forcibly taken away from them by the colonial regime.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Lands and Agriculture had prepared and served
acquisition orders for 841 farms, including those offered to the
government, in fulfillment of a legal requirement, said Msika.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
