<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OSCE Meeting to Focus on Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) Wednesday started its seventh
ministerial council meeting in Oslo, capital of Norway.
</P>
<P>
OSCE chief and Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek and
high-ranking officials from the 54 member nations including 40
foreign ministers are attending in the two-day meeting, which is
expected to focus on the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Norwegian Prime Minister Kjell Magne
Bondevik defended the OSCE, which has been criticized for being
slow in organizing the Kosovo Verification Mission (KVM).
</P>
<P>
Bondevik said, "We must not forget that the KVM is by far the
biggest and most complex field operation in the OSCE's history."
</P>
<P>
Although the OSCE is playing an important role in solving the
Kosovo crisis, a final settlement can only be brought about
through international cooperation and the coordination between the
United Nations, the OSCE, NATO and the six-nation Contact Group is
of utmost importance, he said.
</P>
<P>
Geremek said the peacekeeping operations were the biggest
single challenge for the OSCE.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo crisis demonstrates that small-scale internal armed
confrontation is the most probable conflicts to affect European
security, Geremek said.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE is sending a group of 2,000 observers to monitor a
U.S-brokered truce signed by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
in October.
</P>
<P>
About 400 OSCE observers have so far been deployed in Kosovo, a
province of Serbia, with the rest due by the end of January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
