<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deported Ethiopians from Eritrea to Top 39,075: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Seven hundred Ethiopians
arrived at the northern Rama border Tuesday bringing the total of
those expelled from Eritrea to 36,475, the office of Ethiopian
government spokesperson Selome Taddesse announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The office said in a statement issued here that the 700
deported Ethiopians who were loaded by 15 buses, were greeted at
the border and driven to Adwa where they are being cared for by
the Disaster Prevention and Preparedness Commission of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The office said the age range of those deportees extended from
babies of 3 months old to 70-year-old women.
</P>
<P>
The office said Friday that 600 Ethiopians are expected to
arrive through the border near Humera, in Western Tigray and
between Saturday and Monday another 2,000 will be arriving
through Bure on the Afar-Eritrea border.
</P>
<P>
All of the above will bring the total of Ethiopians expelled
form Eritrea to 39,075, said the office.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, press reports said Wednesday that the United States
Agency for International Development recently donated rations
enough for six months to some 60,000 war-displaced persons in
West Zone of the northern Tigray state.
</P>
<P>
The relief food include 5,458 tons of wheat, 218,350 liters of
cooking oil, 436 tons of lentil and 40,094 sacks of flour.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of African Unity (OAU) Mechanism for Conflict
Prevention, Management and Resolution will hold a summit in
Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso on December 17 and 18 to deliberate
proposals on peaceful solution to the seven-month Ethio-Eritrean
border dispute, among others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
