<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Stresses Jobs During German EU Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- German government stressed
Wednesday that job creation would be the cornerstone of Germany's
1999 European Union (EU) presidency.
</P>
<P>
"The goal is more employment in Europe...," said spokesman of
the German government Uwe-Karsten Heye after a meeting of the
cabinet in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
But Heye did not give any details about what sort of new
measures EU planned to fight joblessness.
</P>
<P>
EU leaders have pledged the battle against joblessness as a top
priority at every one of their semi-annual summits since Essen in
1994.
</P>
<P>
There has been little progress and joblessness in the 15-
nation bloc remains at 10 per cent or about 18 million. Among the
11 euro-members unemployment is almost 11 per cent.
</P>
<P>
Like France, German government wants the EU to set binding job
creation targets for members.
</P>
<P>
Heye said German government's other top priority was reforming
the EU's budget, farm subsidy spending and aid policies - the
so-called Agenda 2000 package. The government hoped these reforms
could be agreed by a special EU summit in Germany next March, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer will visit all E.U. capitals
from December 13 to 18 to outline Bonn's presidency plans.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima
will have talks in Bonn Friday on the upcoming December 11-12
Vienna summit which marks conclusion of Austria's E.U. presidency.
</P>
<P>
Germany will hold the rotating EU presidency from January 1 to
June 30 next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
