<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New-home Sales Continue Growth in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nationwide new-home
sales went up a modest 0.8 percent in October for the second
consecutive month, continuing at a record-setting pace for all of
1998, the Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
New single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 851,000, up from a revised 844,000 the month before,
according to the department. Previously, September sales had been
reported at an 822,000 rate.
</P>
<P>
Low interest rates and strong U.S. economic growth amidst the
world financial chaos are fueling the busiest year for new-home
sales since the department started tracking the data in 1963.
</P>
<P>
Sales are running 8.7 percent ahead of last year's pace, when
804,000 were sold and should easily surpass the record 819,000
sold in 1977.
</P>
<P>
October marked the 14th consecutive month of sales above an
800,000-unit rate, a record. It also marked the 22nd month in a
row that the supply of unsold homes has been less than needed to
meet demand for five months at the current sales rate, which is
also a record.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, all of October's gain came in the West, where sales
jumped 11.2 percent to a rate of 248,000. Sale declined 11 percent
in the Northeast to a rate of 65,000, 5.4 percent in the Midwest
to 157,000 and 0.3 percent to 381,000 in the South.
</P>
<P>
In September, sales fell in the West, picked up in the Midwest
and South and held steady in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
The median price of a new home was 150,000 U.S. dollars in
October, up 6 percent from a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
