<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Agrees to Extension of U.N. Observers' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Angola said here Wednesday it
has agreed to further extension of the United Nations observers
mission to February 1999.
</P>
<P>
Higini Carneiro, deputy head of the government delegation in
Joint Commission for the Angolan Peace Process made the remarks
after talks with delegates of the United Nations and the observer
countries of the United States, Russia and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Carneiro pointed out that his government will stick to its
stance in regard to UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi at the U.N.
Security Council meeting in New York Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government insists that President Savimbi of the
opposite National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
has lost his status as the dialogist in the peace process and the
breakaway UNITA Renovation Commission is the sole lawful
dialogist.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government official admitted that the military
situation in this southern African country is "very tense."
Therefore, he said, the government has demanded that the U.N.
should impose more strict sanctions upon the armed UNITA,
especially in te field of telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
As to the 15 U.N. military observers detained by the UNITA,
Carneiro said that his government has not got any new information
about them.
</P>
<P>
On November 11, the UNITA troops prevented the U.N. personnel
from evacuating Bailundo in central Huambo Province and Andulo in
Bie Province on the ground that they had to "repair" runways at
the airports.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the UNITA held them hostage as shields
against attacks from the government troops.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Ambassador to Luanda Ramalho Ortigao said that the
peace process observers are deeply worried over the incident and
will make their stance clear.
</P>
<P>
On June 30 last year, the U.N. Security Council decided to
send observers to Angola to supervise over the implementation of
the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol which ended the 19-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council decided to extend the observers' term by
six weeks as it expired on October 15 this year.
</P>
<P>
Presently, the council is holding a meeting in New York to
discuss whether to further extend the term of the observers or
not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
