<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Bans Fishing in N. Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The government has decided to
ban fishing in northern province of Cabo Delgado, Mozambican
Health Minister Aurelio Zilhao said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said more than 100 people died after eating
polluted fish and 1,400 others got ill as recorded by the health
department since September this year.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that many people felt sick after eating the
fish polluted by insecticides.
</P>
<P>
According to Zilhao, the chemical analysis of the fishery
products and flour of maize and sorghum shows that the food
contained residuals of insecticides.
</P>
<P>
Besides a 45-day ban of fishing in the province, the
government also decided to "strictly control" the storage and
sale of the insecticides and to set up an inter-ministry team to
probe the incident on the spot and work out a plan to take hold
of the situation.
</P>
<P>
The government will also sensitize local population on
hygiene, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Zilhao noted that what his government must do is to make sure
that no one will die any more.
</P>
<P>
Fish is the staple food for local residents and also the main
currency earner.
</P>
<P>
The health minister disclosed that the Mozambican National
Commission for Emergency is considering delivering alternative
food to the residents in the affected areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
