<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK House Prices Hit by Economic Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) - The economic slowdown has begun
to affect the housing market in Britain with prices falling 0.6
percent in November, according to the latest survey from the
Halifax.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Nationwide Building Society earlier this week
showed the same underlying picture of a downturn in the property
market.
</P>
<P>
It is a big turnaround from October when prices grew 1.3
percent. On annual basis, November's figures show property prices
rising by 4.9 percent - a marked slowdown on the 6.7 percent
annual inflation reported in October.
</P>
<P>
The Halifax survey provides a gloomy picture of the current
state of the housing market that prices had fallen for the first
time in three years.
</P>
<P>
However, the UK's largest mortgage provider believes that the
housing market is not heading for a crash.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the bank said it was difficult to gauge too
much from just one month's figures - a clearer picture of the
housing market emerged from looking at house prices over a
three-month period.
</P>
<P>
Prices in the three months to November were 1.2 percent higher
than in the preceding three months - a similar increase to that
recorded for the three months to September and October.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said: "It is our view that house prices are
likely to rise less steeply in 1999 than this year, as the
expected sharp fall in economic growth is reflected in weaker
demand for housing." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief May Visit Libya Over Lockerbie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan is likely to visit the Libyan capital of Tripoli for
talks with the Libyan authorities on the 10-year-old Lockerbie
issue, a U.N. spokesman said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman, Manoel de Almeida e Silva, told a press
conference that "there is some possibility" for Annan to pay the
visit in order to discuss with Tripoli on the surrender of two
suspects in Lockerbie bombing.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who is in Tunisia Wednesday for a two-day visit, most
likely make a trip to Libya over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"I'm in contact with the authorities of Tripoli and it may
happen that I go there on a visit after visiting Tunis," Annan
told a press conference in Algiers at the end of his tour in
Algeria in a bid to break a deadlock on a U.N.-sponsored peace
process in the Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats in the U.N. headquarters in New York said that Annan
would seek permission of a U.N. Security Council sanctions
committee, which envoys said would be granted immediately.
</P>
<P>
But members of the Libya sanctions committee said they had not
yet received a request through its chairman, Slovenian Permanent
Representative to the United Nations Danilo Turk. Libya has been
under a U.N. air embargo since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Libya has agreed to put the two suspects, namely Abdel Basset
Ali Mohammed al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, on trial in the
Netherlands before a Scottish court. But Tripoli has objected to
British and U.S. demands that they, if convicted, serve their
sentence in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans have been accused by the United States and
Britain of planting a bomb aboard Pan Am Flight 103 which exploded
over the Scottish village of Lockerbie nearly 10 year ago, killing
270 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
