<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duma Asks Kremlin to Report Yeltsin's Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma, or lower
house of parliament, Wednesday adopted a resolution requiring a
statement on President Boris Yeltsin's health, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The resolution passed by a vote of 247 versus 33 with no
abstentions insisted that the Kremlin submit a medical report on
Yeltsin to both houses of parliament within 10 days and ordered
parliamentary committees to ask the Constitutional Court whether
the president may be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
The document was supported by the Communist faction, the
Agrarian faction, the People's Power faction and some of the
members of the Russian Regions group, while Our Home Is Russia,
Yabloko and the Liberal-Democratic Party were against.
</P>
<P>
Liberal Democrat Alexei Mitrofanov, who lead the Duma
Geopolitical committee, said the resolution could produce a
situation where decisions by doctors determine Russia's politics.
</P>
<P>
Boris Misnik of Yabloko said his party opposed the anti-Yeltsin
move "for pragmatic, legal and moral reasons."
</P>
<P>
Today is the eleventh day for the Russian president to have a
treatment in the Central Clinical Hospital. Yeltsin was taken to
the hospital with pneumonia on November 22, when his temperature
rose to 38.9 degrees Centigrade.
</P>
<P>
First deputy head of the presidential administration Yuri Yarov
told reporters Wednesday that Yeltsin is likely to resume work in
the Kremlin on next Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Population Declines Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Russian population is
expected to shrink by one half by the middle of the next century,
the Russian State Committee for Statistics forecast, the Interfax
news agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to figures cited Wednesday at a session of the
presidential commission on the issues of women, family, and
demography in Moscow, Russia's birth rate, which decreased by 6
percent from 1989 to 1997, has hit a world low.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the death rate, up 3.5 percent within the period, is
as high as that of a war embroiled country.
</P>
<P>
Demographers predict that by 2015, Russia's populace will
decrease by 8.6 million to a total of 138 million, and the number
of able-bodied people will decrease by 4.4 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Accuses Turkey of Interfering in Domestic Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Greece on Tuesday accused
neighboring Turkey of interfering in its domestic affairs after
statements made by senior Turkish officials on the issue of the
Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said at a press
briefing that Greece did not allow any third party to interfere in
its domestic affairs. "The governments of Greece and Cyprus are
handling the missile issue responsibly in accordance with their
own needs," he added.
</P>
<P>
To strengthen its defense, Cyprus had earlier last year decided
to purchase the missiles from Russia. Currently, the two
governments of Greece and Cyprus are discussing the location of
the missile deployment with no final decision has been taken.
</P>
<P>
To avoid being dragged into hostilities with Turkey, Greece
proposes that the missiles should be installed in the southern
Greek island of Crete, but Cyprus insists that the missiles will
be deployed on the island republic as planned.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem opposed the idea of the
deployment of the missiles in Crete as an alternative to Cyprus,
saying in Paris recently that Crete belonged to the same
geographical region and he believed that this kind of talks was
not serious.
</P>
<P>
Reppas urged Turkey to be more like Greece with respect to its
achievements on the economic front, the operation of democratic
institutions and respect for individual rights.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greece's Alternate Foreign Minister
George Papandreou also called on Turkey to change its "aggressive
policy" to one of peace and refrain from trying to transfer its
responsibilities to neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
