<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Hails U.N. Statement on Peacekeeping Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry
Wednesday hailed the U.N. Security Council chairman's statement on
peacekeeping activities, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that the statement "is designed to become an
important step towards strengthening the U.N. Security Council's
ability to oversee and ensure effective control over peacekeeping
activities which it sanctions."
</P>
<P>
The statement confirms the Security Council's principal
responsibility for safeguarding global peace and security and says
that "one of the effective ways for the U.N. Security Council to
respond to conflicts could be authorizing actions by regional or
sub-regional organizations, member states or coalitions of
states," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry said that non-U.N. peacekeeping
operations should be carried out in accordance with the principles
of sovereignty, political independence and territorial integrity
of all states and in compliance with the operational principles of
U.N. peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
Russia repeatedly criticized certain Western countries for
taking sanctions without U.N. authorization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report of Congo (K) Rebels' Using Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has strongly refuted an
allegation by a member of parliament that rebels in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) use Ugandan passports in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued Wednesday, Minister of Internal
Affairs Tom Butime said Ugandan passports are issued after a
rigorous vetting process to ensure that applicants are genuine
Ugandans with no criminal records.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed as malicious propaganda allegations by MP Aggrey
Awori who claimed that he met DRC rebels in possession of Ugandan
passports in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Butime said Awori's allegations were purely sensational and
meant to tarnish the image of the government because he could not
give the names and passport numbers of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Citizenship matters cannot be merely judged by physical
appearance, color and language spoken, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said even if the report were true, Awori, as a
prominent and responsible citizen, should have reported cases of
illegal possession of Ugandan passports to Interpol or relevant
authorities for prosecution instead of making such irresponsible
remarks.
</P>
<P>
Awori's allegations appeared in the Monitor newspaper here
Tuesday, sparking associations of Uganda's close relationship
with the rebels fighting to oust DRC President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been accused of fomenting and backing the DRC
rebels, a charge Kampala has denied from the very beginning. It
denies any involvement in the DRC conflict and says its military
presence in eastern DRC is to guarantee its border security only.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
