<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Denies Support for U.S. Proposal over Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdul-Meguid Wednesday denied a report that the AL
supports a U.S.-proposed venue for trying two Libyans accused of
the 1988 Pan Am bombing over Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Meguid, on a visit to Lebanon, told Egypt's Middle East
News Agency that he was astonished by the report, reiterating AL's
support for Libya's position on the Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
The London-based Arabic-language Al Hayat newspaper said on
Wednesday that the AL supports a proposal that the two Libyans be
tried in a U.S. military base in a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
The league sides with Libya over its demand for a guarantee
that its two citizens get a fair trial in a neutral country and
not be handed over to the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have accused the two Libyans of blowing up
the Pan Am 103 flight over Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988, which
killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
For years, Washington and London insisted on trying them
either in the U.S. or Scotland. Fearing that the two will not get
a fair trial in either place, Libya called for a neutral venue.
</P>
<P>
A compromise has been reached in July between the two sides
that the two Libyans will be tried by Scottish judges under
Scottish law in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
But Libya, meanwhile, has demanded guarantees that the two
suspects will not be extradited to the U.S. and wants them to be
imprisoned in Libya if convicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Freezes $36m Loan to Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has suspended the
disbursement of a 36 million U.S. Dollar loan to a water project
in Sierra Leone, a report reaching here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The loan was approved in 1996 to help state-owned Guma Valley
Water Company expand water supply in the capital Freetown, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
A World Bank official in Sierra Leone said Wednesday that it
was agreed that the Sierra Leonean government would install water
meters to ensure the loan is repaid with money generated from
water sales.
</P>
<P>
However, the official said the government has not installed
any meters, hence forcing the bank to suspend the loan until they
are installed.
</P>
<P>
According to the Seirra Lonean company officials, the bank has
only disbursed seven million dollars of the loan total so far and
that only a fifth of the project has been done.  
</P>
</TEXT>
