<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Biological Team Meets Iraqi Side </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A biological team of the
U.N. Special Commission for disarming Iraq (UNSCOM) met with the
Iraqi side on Wednesday, reported the Iraqi News Agency INA.
</P>
<P>
Hussam Mohammed Ameen, head of the Iraqi liaison with UNSCOM,
was quoted as saying that the meeting was held at the building of
the Iraqi National Monitoring Directorate, which provides
government escorts for the U.N. teams, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The biological weapons inspection team, headed by David Kelly
of Britain, arrived in Baghdad on Tuesday, along with a
U.N. missile monitoring team.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM has long demanded that Iraq provide more documents on
its biological weapons program, but Iraq insists that it has
handed over all the documents concerning its proscribed weapons to
UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official said that U.N. inspectors continued their
work on Wednesday. Nine groups from UNSCOM and the International
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) conducted routine or surprise
inspections to 13 Iraqi sites, five of which are not under
long-term monitoring.
</P>
<P>
He said some of these groups reached their destinations by
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Since Iraq resumed cooperation with UNSCOM two weeks ago,
U.N. arms inspections have been going on smoothly with  no
incidents reported occurred so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
