<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Never Allows Anyone to Dictate Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will never allow anyone
to dictate its defense policy, said Cypriot government spokesman
Christos Stylianides on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a statement by Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem,
the spokesman said "we do not have masters dictating to us the way
we should deal with issues concerning our defense."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Cem said that Turkey objected to a possible
deployment of the Russian S-300 missiles, which Cyprus has
ordered, on the Greek island of Crete.
</P>
<P>
He warned that "if they make such a mistake, there will be
serious repercussions."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a deal with Russia in January 1997 to buy
anti-aircraft S-300 missiles in a bid to boost its defense
capability.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and other western countries have criticized Cyprus
for signing the deal, and Turkey has threatened to launch
pre-emptive military strikes if the missiles are deployed on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus welcomes any initiative within the framework of
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's mission of good offices in
Cyprus aimed at the demilitarization of the island, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Cypriot government joins in the shuttle talks
undertaken by U.N. resident representative in Cyprus Ann Hercus,
which are within this framework.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in 1974
following a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which was recognized only
by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-communal formula, but no results have been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
