<HEADLINE> World Bank Donates Vehicles to Uganda's Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has donated 32
vehicles to Uganda's Lake Victoria Environment Management Project
to facilitate its implementation.
</P>
<P>
The vehicles were handed over to Henry Kajura, the Ugandan
Minister of Water, Land and Environment, by the World Bank
Representative Randolph Harri here Wednesday, the Uganda News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The provision of vehicles, together with equipment and labs,
mark the completion of the phase one of the project which,
started in 1997, was set up to manage, regulate and ensure the
protection of Lake Victoria and its catchment areas in the three
east African countries-- Uganda, Tanzania and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
At the handover ceremony, the bank official said the
sustainable management of the lake as an important natural
economic resource for the region was the reason behind the bank's
funding for the project.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the bank's hope that the end result of
implementing the project will be eradication of poverty in the
catchment area of the lake on which over 20 million people are
dependent for their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
The minister thanked the World Bank for its start-up support
for the project and asked the project managers to make good use
of the vehicles which go to 10 components of the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
