<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Europe to Speed Return of Jewish Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States asked
European countries Wednesday to return to Jewish groups the
synagogues, schools, cemeteries, community centers and artifacts
that were plundered by the Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
"Governments improperly took this property from the rightful
owners without compensation," Stuart Eizenstat, undersecretary of
state, told an international conference.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the conference on Holocaust-era assets, Eizenstat
said, "Now it is our common responsibility to ensure that,
finally, justice is done."
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat said communal property, from religious land,
buildings, artifacts and documents such as the Torah was "one of
the early targets of the Nazi regime" of wartime Germany.
</P>
<P>
Private property also was stolen, and although the conference
didn't address it, Eizenstat urged European nations to "make a
start" in settling private claims through return or restitution.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat cited obstacles across Europe, including slow-moving
governments, legal problems at the local level and the question of
making restitution to current owners.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting, which ends Thursday, involves 44
countries, the Vatican and more than a dozen groups, including
those representing Jewish, art, history and insurance interests.
</P>
<P>
The conference, sponsored by the U.S. State Department and the
Holocaust Museum in Washington, is aimed at setting informal
standards for returning looted art and propertys.
</P>
<P>
The Nazis looted an estimated 150,000 pieces of art from
Western Europe during the war and some 500,000 pieces from Eastern
and Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
Ronald Lauder, chairman of the board of the Museum of Modern
Art and an official with the World Jewish Congress, estimated
110,000 pieces of art worth 10 billion to 30 billion U.S. dollars
are still missing and said virtually every large museum,
institution and private collection contains some.
</P>
<P>
A review of 225 museum catalogs over the Summer by his group
found 1,700 looted pieces of art, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lauder called on governments and museums to return the art or
auction it to help Jewish groups and Holocaust survivors and their
families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
