<HEADLINE> Egypt, Iraq to Sign Memo of Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Iraq are expected to
sign next week a memorandum of understanding on bilateral
cooperation, an official of Egypt's Trade and Supply Ministry said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told Egypt's
Middle East News Agency that the memo will be signed during a
three-day visit to Egypt by Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi
Saleh, who will arrive here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili will
discuss with Saleh ways of promoting cooperation in the field of
technology and telecommunications, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers will co-chair a meeting of the Egyptian-Iraqi
Trade Committee, during which both sides will discuss ways of
enhancing cooperation in trade, transport and electricity.
</P>
<P>
The committee meeting will be held in line with a memo of
cooperation in economy and trade, signed during Gowaili's visit to
Iraq in June, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt exported 238 million U.S. dollars worth of goods to Iraq
in the first eight months of 1998 under the oil-for-food program
between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The program allows Iraq, which is under U.N. economic
sanctions, to sell a limited amount of oil to buy food, medicine
and other humanitarian good for its people. 
</P>
