<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Helps Tanzania Eradicate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The African Development
Bank (ADB) has approved 12 million U.S. Dollars for the
establishment of a Small Entrepreneurs Loan Facility (SELF) in
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Edward Lowassa, the Minister of State in the Vice-President's
Office, said Tuesday in the central city of Dodoma that the
facility will provide soft loans to people with low incomes.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a three-day national workshop on poverty
eradication and environmental conservation being chaired by
President Benjamin Mkapa, Lowassa said SELF is intended to
integrate and strengthen micro-finance institutions providing
soft loans, including non governmental organizations (NGOs),
credit and savings schemes and the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here Wednesday, Lowassa said SELF will
start operating in the middle of next month and provide loans to
groups, individuals, small-scale farmers and jobless youths in
towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
At present, 50 percent of Tanzanians are living on poverty
line, said Lowassa, who challenged responsible ministries, towns
and district councils to create conducive environment for private
investors to create employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
He said sectors like public works programs could be
implemented by employing villagers in their respective areas so
that they could expand financial resources.
</P>
<P>
Lowassa also said the Vice-President's Office has started
preparing poverty monitoring indicators which would determine the
extent of poverty in various sectors.
</P>
<P>
The move will also help the government know whether its various
poverty eradication programs have been successful or not, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lowassa told the workshop with the presence of the entire
national leadership that the government has so far dished out 300
billion Shillings (about 444 million U.S. Dollars) to various
development funds in a bid to fight poverty.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, opened by founder of the nation Julius Nyerere,
is being attended by Zanzibar President Salmin Amour, Tanzanian
Vice-President Omar Ali Juma, all ministers and their deputies,
regional and district commissioners and local authorities
functionaries.
</P>
<P>
It is jointly sponsored by the government, Danish embassy,
United States Agency for International Development (USAID),
United Nations Development Program and BP (T) Limited. 
</P>
