<HEADLINE> UK Promises Libya Access if Lockerbie Bombers Jailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Kingdom promised
Wednesday that Libya could station an unrestricted consular to the
two Libyans who are suspected of being responsible for the
Lockerbie bombing, if they were jailed in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The UK government, which is seeking to persuade Libyan leader
Muammar Gaddafi to hand over the two suspects, made the promise
several days earlier.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office spokesman told journalists Wednesday that the
promise had been relayed through U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, who is expected to visit Libya this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said London would not move on the principle that
the men had to serve their sentences in Scotland but could make
some compromise in response to Libyan questions.
</P>
<P>
It is not known yet what Gaddafi's response would be.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans were accused by both the United States and the
UK of planting a bomb aboard a Pan American airliner on December
21, 1988. The plane exploded over the Scottish town of Lockerbie
and killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, London and Washington agreed that the two
could be tried in the Hague of the Netherlands, but by Scottish
judges. Libya has agreed to this plan in principle.
</P>
<P>
But Libyan leader Gaddafi said Sunday that the UK and the U.S.
were still trying to impose unacceptable conditions and were
refusing to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
The UK spokesman said that if the two were found guilty, they
must serve their sentence in Scotland, but Libya could be allowed
to keep consular officials in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
They would have special access to prison to ensure that the men
were treated properly under arrangements which could be made under
U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council imposed an air and arms
embargo on Libya in 1992, and expanded it in 1993 to include a
freeze on some Libyan assets abroad and a ban on some oil
equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
