<HEADLINE> Judge Allows House Impeachment Investigators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. judge allowed
Wednesday the House of Representatives' Judiciary Committee access
to memos on fund raising during President Bill Clinton's 1996
re-election campaign, but Democrats said the move was a sign the
panel's inquiry was out of control.
</P>
<P>
Chief U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson ruled that one
Republican and one Democratic staff member could see the internal
Justice Department memos, but could not make copies or take notes
and must report the contents only to Chairman Henry Hyde and
ranking Democrat John Conyers.
</P>
<P>
The committee had sought copies of the memos, but Republicans
said the ruling was a positive move.
</P>
<P>
The memos, written by FBI Director Louis Freeh and former
campaign finance task force head Charles LaBella, include
confidential information from grand juries under Johnson's
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
They have long been sought by Congress but Attorney General
Janet Reno refused to let congressional investigators see them,
even after she was cited for contempt by the Republican-controlled
House Government Reform and Oversight Committee earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Republicans said they had received information the memos might
contain evidence of criminal wrongdoing by Clinton, and that they
were "duty-bound" to investigate. They have also subpoenaed Freeh
and LaBella to give closed-door depositions.
</P>
<P>
But House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt, speaking to
reporters on Wednesday after meeting with Clinton at the White
House, said Hyde was giving in to committee conservatives and that
House leaders were not asserting leadership of the probe.
</P>
<P>
"We are in chaos in the House on impeachment," Gephardt told
reporters shortly before Johnson's ruling.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's chaos. I think no one is in charge. The present
speaker is not exerting leadership. The speaker-to-be is not
exerting leadership, and Henry Hyde seems to be giving in to some
members of the committee."
</P>
<P>
Gephardt sent outgoing Speaker Newt Gingrich and incoming
Speaker Bob Livingston a letter on Tuesday asking them to take
control of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
"So unless leadership on the part of the speaker or the
speaker-to-be comes into this issue in the next few days, I think
there's a serious possibility that this will go into next year,"
Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
But Hyde said on Tuesday he was determined to stick to his
year-end deadline for concluding the probe and hoped to stay on
schedule for a committee vote next week on articles of impeachment
against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
But he said the schedule could be prolonged if the campaign
finance inquiries turned up new information.
</P>
<P>
The confidential memos by LaBella and Freeh unsuccessfully
advocated the appointment of an independent counsel to look into
alleged campaign finance violations during the 1996 Clinton-Gore
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Judge Johnson said in her three-page ruling that it would be
"in the public interest" to allow limited disclosure of the secret
grand jury information in the memos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Economic Growth Rates for 1998-2000 Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Wednesday
predicted that growth rates for developing nations in 1998-2000
will be the lowest since the debt crisis of the 1980s, but that
outlook is likely to improve in 2000.
</P>
<P>
In its ninth annual report on the global economy, "the Global
Economic Prospects and the Developing Countries 1998/99," the
World Bank said that developing countries would be hardest hit by
the economic and social costs of global slowdown in 1998-2000,
with their per capita growth expected to slow to 0.4 percent in
1998, compared with 3.2 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, Indonesia, Russia and 33 other developing and
transition countries, which account for 42 percent of total GDP
for the developing world, and more than a quarter of its
population, are likely to see negative per capita growth this
year. In 1997, by comparison, per capita income fell in 21
countries which accounted for 10 percent of the developing world's
GDP and 7 percent of its population. Although 1999 is likely to be
another year of slow growth in developing countries, their
situation could improve in 2000, and following years, when their
per capita growth could return to the 3.5 percent pace of recent
years (excluding transition economies).
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's new report attributed much of the slowdown in
developing countries to the unprecedented depth and severity of
the recession in the crisis countries of East Asia and its
contagion effect on the rest of the world. With output projected
to decline sharply in the region this year, and to stabilize in
1999, the report noted that the Asian crisis already ranks with
the Latin American debt crisis of the 1980s in terms of its impact
on countries during its first 12 months.
</P>
<P>
Developing nations have been hurt by Japan's deepening
home-grown recession, as well as by a series of shocks related to
the Asian crisis. These include: the collapse of the Russian
ruble, falling commodity prices, a marked slowdown in world import
demand, and general risk aversion in financial markets. Besides,
El Nino-related phenomena also brought both severe flooding and
drought to many parts of Africa, Asia and Latin America,
devastating crops, water supplies and rural infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Worldwidely, output growth is expected to be cut nearly half,
from 3.2 percent in 1997 to 1.8 percent in 1998, and to revive
only modestly to 1.9 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, Joseph E. Stiglitz, the World Bank senior vice
president and chief economist, said, "While 1998 and 1999 will be
very difficult years for developing countries, in the longer term
(2001-2007), growth in developing countries could still reach the
record setting rates that we saw in 1991-1997. But this will only
happen if policies to prevent a deeper global slump are
implemented quickly and developing countries strengthen their
financial sectors." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Premier-Designate Profile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's veteran politician
Salim Hoss was designated Wednesday by the newly-elected
President Emile Lahoud as the new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Hoss, who turns 69 on December 20, is known for his background
in economics and his three terms as prime minister during the
country's 1975-1990 civil war, in contrast to outgoing premier
Rafik Hariri's reputation as the successful contractor of the
reconstruction era.
</P>
<P>
Hoss presided over three cabinets. He also served as education
and labor minister from 1985 to 1987 and has sat in parliament
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Much of Hoss's appeal derives from his reputation as an
honest lawmaker, and he enjoys support from professionals and
intellectuals around the country, while his criticism of
Hariri's social and economic policies has been characterized as
"constructive."
</P>
<P>
His experience outside politics has been split evenly between
academics and finance. He served as a member of the World Bank's
consultative board for the Middle East and North Africa between
1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Before the civil war, Hoss was a financial expert with the
Kuwaiti Fund for Arab Economic Development and presided over the
Banking Control Commission at Lebanon's Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, he was a consultant for the Arab Monetary
Fund in the United Arab Emirates, as well as chairman of
the board of the Arab and International Investment Bank.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1929, Hoss is the youngest of five children of a lower
middle class Sunni family from Beirut. His father, a pharmacist,
died when he was young.
</P>
<P>
Despite financial strains, he studied business at the
prestigious American University of Beirut, where he later
taught for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
His 10 books include a two-volume autobiography and several
works on business administration and economics.
</P>
<P>
Hoss has one daughter, Wadad, by his late wife Leila
Pharaon, who died in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
