<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Sharif Meet on Nuclear, F-16 Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif Wednesday met over
Pakistan's nuclear policies and to review a plan for returning
some of 658 million U.S. dollars owed to Pakistan for F-16 fighter
jets it never received.
</P>
<P>
In remarks to reporters before the talks, Clinton praised
Sharif for resuming direct talks with India on the Kashmir
conflict and said he would consider playing a mediating role if
both nations asked him.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told reporters he planned to brief Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif on U.S. efforts to compensate Islamabad for
the money it paid for 28 F-16s which it never received because of
U.S. sanctions imposed in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The two also focused on the tit-for-tat nuclear tests India and
Pakistan conducted earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
"All of you know of my concern to do everything we can to end
the nuclear competition in South Asia, which I believe is a threat
to Pakistan and India and to the stability of the world," Clinton
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told reporters that he is hoping to visit the two
countries next year.
</P>
<P>
Just on the eve of Sharif's visit, Clinton Tuesday temporarily
waived certain economic sanctions imposed on India and Pakistan
after the nuclear tests in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
