<HEADLINE> Germany, France Cut Key Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The central banks of Germany and
France Thursday cut key interest rates by 0.3 percent to 3.0
percent.
</P>
<P>
The German Bundesbank lowered its securities repurchase rate to
3.0 percent from 3.3 percent, which has been unchanged since
October 1997.
</P>
<P>
The bank left two other main interest rates, the Lombard rate and
the discount rate, unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The French central bank cut its money market lending rate by
0.3 percent from 3.3 per cent.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that other euro zone central banks, including
the Spanish, Dutch, Belgian, Portuguese, Finnish, Irish and
Austrian central banks, all took their key rates down to three
percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
European stocks shot up and currencies fell in response to the
surprise decision by the countries in the euro single currency
zone to make concerted interest rate cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
