<HEADLINE> Russian Government Approves Plan on Stabilization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government Thursday
approved an action plan to stabilize the social and economic
situation in the country, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
At a regular session of the government, Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said that without the action plan the measures outlined
by the government would look like nothing but intentions.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said the plan was "oriented toward executive bodies at
all levels."
</P>
<P>
Minister of Economy Andrei Shapovalyants said the plan sets out
 "urgent measures to stabilize the situation...so as to ensure,
starting from May, economic growth by the end of 1999."
</P>
<P>
By working out the plan, the government "created a mechanism to
help buffer negative processes taking place in the financial
sphere, which include a reduction in the population's income and
in tax collections," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Shapovalyants said the plan includes three main sections that
deal with establishing normal living conditions for the
population, prerequisites for stabilizing the economy, as well as
measures to restore and develop the real estate sector.
</P>
<P>
The plan, in its final form, will be made public on Saturday,
according to the minister. 
</P>
