<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Auditing Offices Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The National Audit Office of
China (CNAO) has uncovered 9.6 billion yuan (1.16 billion
U.S. dollars) in irregular funds which have been surrendered
to the public finance.
</P>
<P>
Li Jinhua, China's auditor general, noted that his office is
focusing its attention on the auditing of enterprises, the grain
distribution system, and securities companies.
</P>
<P>
The CNAO auditors have reviewed the accuracy, compliance and
effectiveness of the 1997 revenues and expenditures of 23 large
and medium-size state-owned enterprises, and 162 key loss-making
state-owned enterprises in seven provinces and autonomous
regions including Hebei, Inner Mongolia and Shandong.
</P>
<P>
Problems including false disclosure of assets, liabilities,
profits and losses have been discovered in the course of the
audits.
</P>
<P>
False disclosure of assets has reached 11.2 billion yuan (1.35
billion dollars), false liabilities 4.5 billion yuan (540 million
dollars), and false profits and losses 3.7 billion yuan (445
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Auditors have detected 1,181 cases of financial and economic
laws and regulations violations during the audit of the grain
distribution system. And among those responsible, 166 have been
punished by Party or administrative discipline, while 27 have been
investigated for criminal liability.
</P>
<P>
The CNAO has set up 102,000 auditing branches throughout the
country since it was established, and the number of auditors
nationwide has reached 270,000.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the audit offices always emphasize the importance
of earnestly implementing the strategy of governing the nation in
accordance with law, and they have plans to create 45 auditing
regulations by the end of this century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
