<HEADLINE> Syrian Parliamentary Election Results Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Two hundred and fifty men and
women candidates has won their seats in Syria's seventh
parliamentary elections, Syrian Interior Minister mohammad Harba
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 815 woman candidates, 26 turned out to be members of the
250-seat People's Council, or the parliament, winning two more
seats for women in the parliament as compared to the previous
term. And 76 MPs retained their posts, Harba told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
The new council is seen as covering all sectors of society, as
members are from various backgrounds including workers, farmers,
intellectuals, jurists, doctors, engineers, artists.
</P>
<P>
There were about 7,361 candidates from 15 electoral
constituencies. Out of the 6,691,323 registered voters, 5,501,940
exercised their rights by casting their votes, a turnout rate of
82.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The elections took place from November 30 to December 1.
</P>
