<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Opening of Internet Service Sector (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- China's largest Internet-based
news service signed an agreement today with a major
telecommunications company for long-term cooperation in
Internet-related services.
</P>
<P>
The pact between China Internet Information Center (CIIC),
under the State Council Information Office, and GTE Corp. of the
United States is the first China has entered into for Internet
development services.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement will allow CIIC to more easily provide
information about China to Web users in North America and
Europe using GTE's network," said Bruce Linton, vice-president of
sales and marketing for GTE Internetworking Services.
</P>
<P>
Of the 2 million visitors to the CIIC website, which started
operation on Jan. 1, 1997, one-quarter are Internet users in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Experts say this is an important step toward the opening of
China's Web content service.
</P>
<P>
But this agreement is not such big news in the country's
Internet service sector, as a number of agreements and contracts
between China's Internet service providers and foreign firms have
already attracted the spotlight in the Internet community.
</P>
<P>
Yahoo recently concluded its agreement with Infoshare
Technology Co., Ltd. affiliated with China's Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Infoshare will help market Yahoo's
services in China, and the latter will promote Chinese businesses
and help them with online advertising.
</P>
<P>
Yahoo expects to open its Beijing office next year.
</P>
<P>
There is ample reason for the world's major networking and
Internet service companies to be optimistic about the China market.
</P>
<P>
The latest information shows that Internet users nationwide has
now reached 1.2 million, and is doubling every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Opening of Internet Service Sector (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Early this year, a delegation of top executives from major
U.S. Internet service providers visited China; and U.S. president
Bill Clinton made a trip to the Internet Cafe in Shanghai during
his state visit to China this past summer.
</P>
<P>
Now, hundreds of China's Internet service firms are seeking
cooperation from foreign counterparts for an injection of
technologies and a wider variety of information.
</P>
<P>
The country's most profitable Web content provider, China.com
Corp., has become the exclusive agent for America Online, and has
a firm cooperative relationship with 24/7 Media of the U.S. The
Chinese corporation is working with Netscape right now to produce
a Chinese website.
</P>
<P>
The impact of all this transmission of Internet information
is obviously felt by Chinese. Currently, there are hundreds of
thousands of Yahoo users in China, and more and more Chinese
business people are approaching Yahoo to discuss the possibility
of online advertising.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government limits the involvement of overseas
investment in electronic publications, and stipulates by
regulation that the Chinese side in a joint venture must be the
majority shareholder. And overseas investment is not allowed to
enter the mass media.
</P>
<P>
Like everywhere else in the world, industry analysts say,
government policies and regulations cannot keep up with China's
Internet market expansion, despite a few regulations related to
Internet operations and security which have come into effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
