<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Vows to Develop Multi- and Bilateral Business Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- China will develop multi- and
bilateral commercial ties as it strives to create a sound economic
environment for reforms, opening-up and modernization.
</P>
<P>
Shi Guangsheng, Chinese minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC), made this remark in a speech to Chinese
economic and commercial counsellors working in more than 150
countries, who were attending a conference today on foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Shi said he hopes Chinese commercial officials abroad will
continue to promote multi- and bilateral commercial ties, enhance
research, and offer valuable information and suggestions for the
development of economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
In spite of potentially difficult prospects next year, China
will work hard to expand trade volume and maintain a high level of
overseas capital use, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He called for greater efforts to promote the negotiation
process on China's entry into the World Trade Organization next
year.
</P>
<P>
China will also take an active part in APEC and the
Asia-Europe Meeting to propel free trade and investment among APEC
members and increase economic and technological cooperation among
the Asia-Pacific region and Asia and Europe, he added.
</P>
<P>
China's trade volume totaled 259.1 billion U.S. dollars in the
first ten months this year, up 0.4 percent over the same period of
1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 16,000 new foreign-funded enterprises have been
approved this year, involving contract capital of 35.9 billion
dollars, according to Shi.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that many surrounding countries suffer
from serious economic depression, devalued currencies, and
declining trade volume, but China has scored its achievements
without devaluing its yuan, and this describes a sharp contrast.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
