<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dons Face FA Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Football Association of
England have demanded an urgent explanation from Wimbledon after
an apparent admission by manager Joe Kinnear that Dons players
had broken strict rules on betting.
</P>
<P>
Players at the club could face misconduct charges, fines and
even suspensions if there is any truth in Kinnear's comments
following his side's Worthington Cup quarter-final victory
against Chelsea on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
After the game, Kinnear, said: "We were 66-1 (to win the cup) a
t the start of the season and I think a few of the lads had a few
quid on."
</P>
<P>
Kinnear is known for making flippant comments from time to
time and may argue he is unaware of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
But if it is found that any Dons players did put money on the c
lub to win the competition, it would be in clear contravention of
the tightened regulations on betting in the game drawn up by the
FA last year.
</P>
<P>
The regulations followed a report by Sir John Smith in the
wake of the collapse of the match-fixing case in which Bruce
Grobbelaar, John Fashanu and Hans Segers were all cleared, which
declared that no betting of any kind would be allowed.
</P>
<P>
An FA spokesman said: "We are writing to Wimbledon for a full
explanation.
</P>
<P>
"The rules state that it shall be deemed to be misconduct to
bet on any football match, other than those registered for the
football pools."
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon could technically be kicked out of the competition
if they are found to have broken FA rules, but it is far more
likely that any guilty players would be fined or even suspended.
</P>
<P>
Following Sir John's report, the FA issued a blanket ban on
all types of betting by players, managers and directors - even if
it was on their own team winning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
