<HEADLINE> Annan to Visit Libya Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan said here Thursday that he would visit Libya on
Saturday to discuss the Lockerbie issue with Libyan government
officials.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived here Wednesday on a two-day visit during his
tour of the Arab Moghreb states, said he would meet Libyan
leader Muammar Gaddafi to discuss ways of settling the Lockerbie
issue.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed arms and travel embargo on
Libya since 1992 for its refusal to hand over two Libyans
suspected of blowing up an American airliner over Lockerbie,
Scotland, in 1988, which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council passed a resolution in August calling for
lifting the sanction once Libya agrees to transfer the two
suspects to the Netherlands for trial under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
Libya demanded that, if found guilty, the two Libyans serve
their time in Dutch prisons whereas the United States and Britain
insist they must serve the sentence in British prisons. 
</P>
