<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Joins Energy Charter Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia became the 51st
member state of the Energy Charter Conference after it signed the
Energy Charter Treaty on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia is the second Asian country after Japan to have
acceded to this inter-governmental organization dealing with
energy issues. Both Asian countries still need to ratify the
accession to the treaty that entered into force in April this year.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Charter Treaty provides market-oriented rules for
all economic activities in the energy sector and covers all energy
forms such as oil, gas, electricity, nuclear and renewable
energies.
</P>
<P>
It aims at protecting investment in the energy sector,
facilitating the transit of energy and energy products, settling
disputes, promoting cooperation and supporting structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
Most of the member states of the conference are from Europe due
to the fact that the conference developed from the European Energy
Charter which was a declaration by 53 countries.
</P>
<P>
Signatories were later extended to other areas of the world to
include Australia, Japan and Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
Henning Christophersen, the newly elected chairman of the
conference, said on Thursday that there was a prospect to include
China into the multinational organization as well by first
offering it an observer status.
</P>
<P>
Christophersen said the next task of the conference would move
from ratification to implementation of the treaty by emphasizing
the treaty's purpose to all signatories as an energy development
tool. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
