<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Street Democracy in Guangzhou (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lai Chaohui, president of today's forum, said that many people
were scared to speak a word when the forum was first open in
1992. Most of them just watched and waited, he said.
</P>
<P>
"But gradually they became brave. Sometimes, some people
don't even want to pass the loudspeaker on to someone else," Lai
said.
</P>
<P>
However, there is occasional trouble. Lai recalled that at one
forum on reconstructing the old city district a man shifted the
topic to his family quarrels.
</P>
<P>
"One of the most dramatical changes is the behavior of the
officials attending the forum," Lai said.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning, when officials heard sharp criticism,
the muscles on their faces twisted, Lai said. Now, they listen with
honest expressions, and sometimes even make timely decisions
on sensitive issues.
</P>
<P>
Some government departments even apply to take part in the
discussions, and officials believe they might even hear some good
suggestions from the public, according to Lai.
</P>
<P>
"The street discussion is a new form of democracy in China,"
said sociologist Qiu Haixiong. "It will help improve public
supervision of the government, and increase the transparency of
government work."
</P>
<P>
Some observers believe that the forum signals
something. Guangzhou, along with other cities in China's most
economically prosperous province of Guangdong, are usually seen as
testing grounds for China's reforms.
</P>
<P>
The forum has also attracted officials from dozens of
inland provinces observing the event.
</P>
<P>
Today's discussion ended at 10:30 in the morning. But the
officials were still surrounded by many people.
</P>
<P>
The whole story of this discussion forum will be presented on
the Guangzhou TV Station.
</P>
<P>
The city has decided that the forum will be held regularly
beginning next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Street Democracy in Guangzhou (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Today's topic was "should the
hospital help a brave person if he or she is wounded in a fight
against hooligans, but has no money".
</P>
<P>
The question sparked controversial answers among hundreds of
citizens and officials at a square in downtown Guangzhou, capital
of south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
"To give medical treatment to such sort person is our
responsibility," firmly replied one doctor.
</P>
<P>
"But why not first listen to what our official says?" someone
else suggested.
</P>
<P>
"Aha, from my point of view, hospitals have their
difficulties," said an official with the City Health Bureau. "It
is hard to tell a good man from a person fond of street
fighting. There isn't any law for us to follow in this respect."
</P>
<P>
......
</P>
<P>
The "Yangcheng Forum" is how the people describe this street
discussion, the only forum open to everybody who wants to say
something in public.
</P>
<P>
Since it was inaugurated six years ago, the forum has become a
special channel for Guangzhou citizens to air their views on state
affairs and local issues, and comment on the behavior of officials.
</P>
<P>
The topics are usually decided by the City People's Congress
and the Guangzhou TV Station, the sponsors of the forum, and
municipal officials are required to be on the spot so the
citizens can talk with them face to face.
</P>
<P>
"The forum provides us with an opportunity to discuss pressing
issues as equals with high ranking government officials," said
Tang Guifang, a 55-year-old woman who had made the first speech at
today's forum.
</P>
<P>
She added that in ancient times Chinese citizens had to
prostrate themselves when attempting to talk to imperial
officials.
</P>
<P>
As an enthusiastic participant, the woman has taken part in
discussions on many topics including city environment, food and
health and housing problems.
</P>
<P>
"Usually, problems discussed at the forum are subsequently
solved. What is more important is that I feel I am the master of
the city when taking part in the discussion," said Tang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Baptist University Awards Honorary Doctorates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Guangzhao, a world-known
Chinese physicist, was awarded an honorary doctorate here Thursday
by the Hong Kong Baptist University.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
Tung Chee Hwa officiated at the conferment ceremony of honorary
doctorates to Zhou and three other outstanding persons here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, once president of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, was
awarded an honorary degree of doctor of science. The conferment
was to acknowledge his achievement in physics and his contribution
to the advancement of science and technology in China, said the
University.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Zhou said: "Whether for a long-term
purposes or just to enhance the current international
competitiveness of Chinese industries, plans have to be made to
develop science, technology, education, and various industries
propelled by scientific and technological advancement, including
the service industries. This is a step forward which both the
mainland and Hong Kong must take."
</P>
<P>
Lu Ping, former director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs
Office, was given an honorary degree of doctor of laws for
his contribution to the return of Hong Kong to China.
</P>
<P>
British Professor Peter Newmark, a leader in the world of
translation studies, was awarded an honorary degree of doctor of
letters; Chinese mathematician Wang Yuan was given the honorary
degree of doctor of science in recognition of his brilliant
accomplishment in mathematics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
