<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   WTO Calls For Collective Action Against Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization
(WTO) has urged all countries, even if they are not WTO members,
to take a collective responsibility to deal with the financial and
economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"This crisis calls for a sense of collective responsibility, as
urgently as at any other time in the post-war period," said the
WTO in its 1998 annual report published here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The WTO has suggested that three matters should be addressed
from the perspective of the global trading system.
</P>
<P>
It requires a clear and continuing commitment by governments to
the multilateral trading system and a firm resolve to resist
protectionism. A fresh impetus toward trade liberalization would
contribute to the resolution of the crisis and would send a
positive signal to the markets, the WTO said.
</P>
<P>
It also requires renewed efforts to bring the countries which
are outside the system, including China and Russia, into the
WTO. It would help complete the global economic architecture for
which the need has been so strongly demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
The WTO said in the past that governments have sometimes
responded to recession and rising unemployment by implementing
policies that restrict imports of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
"History tells us that this has been a major mistake," it
pointed out: "The growing economic crisis of the late 1920s became
a full-blown recession when governments closed their borders to
trade, making the pain more severe and the recovery slower."
</P>
<P>
Today, the WTO went on, with national economies ever more
connected, and with 25 percent of global output now being
exported, a resort to protectionism would be more costly still.
</P>
<P>
"Resisting protectionism is vital, but it is not enough," the
WTO said. "Pressing on with trade liberalization is essential to
restoring health to the world economy."
</P>
<P>
"Global trade in goods and services is the circulatory system
of the world economy," it stressed. "If this system fails, the
patient will not improve, no matter which macroeconomic medicine
is prescribed."
</P>
<P>
The continued dynamism of the trading system is a necessary
precondition for economic recovery in Asia and for buttressing the
economies of Russia, Latin America and other parts of the world,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The WTO also pointed out that admitting new members to the
organization would enhance its ability to provide a stable
foundation for the global trading system, particularly during
times of economic stress.
</P>
<P>
"The current crisis makes no distinction between WTO members
and others, and we can't afford to maintain a situation where
millions of people and their governments are outside the benefits
and responsibilities of the trading system," the WTO stated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
