<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Foreign Firms' Choice for Regional Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has increasingly
become the choice for foreign firms to set up their regional
establishments including headquarters and procurement centers.
</P>
<P>
A total of 42 operational headquarters and 22 international
procurement centers for regional establishments in Malaysia have
so far been approved, Malaysian International Trade and Industry
Minister Rafidah Aziz said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government has also approved 802 representative
offices, of which 178 between 1997 and November 1998, and 427
regional offices for foreign companies, of which 46 during the
same period, she said at a function in Petaling Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, with its cost competitiveness, good infrastructure
and support facilities, can serve the regional market efficiently
and competitively, she said.
</P>
<P>
Under the government's program for such companies,
international procurement centers are allowed to maintain
expatriate staff and foreign currency accounts and they can also
bring in raw materials and finished products without having to pay
duties to tax-free industrial zones and licensed manufacturing
warehouses for re-packaging, cargo consolidation and integration
before final distribution.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said operational headquarters are levied a 10-percent
concessionary tax on income arising from qualifying services
rendered to companies outside Malaysia and from interest and
royalties.
</P>
<P>
She said that in addition to maintaining expatriate staff and
foreign currency accounts, these operational headquarters can
borrow up to 10 million ringgit (about 2.631 million U.S. dollars)
from domestic sources without requiring approval from Bank Negara
(State Bank) Malaysia and obtain credit facilities in foreign
currencies.
</P>
<P>
They are also allowed to invest in foreign securities and lend
to related companies outside Malaysia, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Prepares for Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The euro will be introduced
early next month and China is actively making preparation for both
trade and banking in the new currency.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the euro will provide both opportunities
and challenges for China which expects to gain more ground in
trade talks due to European Union's (EU) earnestness for providing
support. China will also be able to raise additional low cost
funds by issuing Eurobonds on a unified capital market and will
quite likely attract increased European investments due to the
elimination of risk involved in the volatile exchange rate,
according to Chinese experts.
</P>
<P>
However, introduction of the euro will also present new
challenges in terms of adjusting the structure of foreign exchange
reserves and foreign debt, as well as expanding trade with the EU
and competing with new financial services related to the currency.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to expand bilateral trade with the EU and
the nation's foreign trade companies are currently training to
ease adjustments to the new currency, according to officials from
the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Chinese banks are also expected to revise expansion strategies
in Europe and will shift their focus to Frankfurt rather than
London. They will also open more branches in European nations
outside the domain of the euro and will compete for related
services.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Bank of China has restructured its foreign
business operations and is fully prepared to offer new services
beginning next month.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts expect that the euro may be weak at the initial
stage but will become strong in the long-term. They suggest that
China may hold at least a portion of long-term debt in the euro
and use various financial instruments to minimize the devaluation
risks for short-term debts in the currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Cut Market Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will cut market
interest rates in a bid to help its economy out of slump, said the
Bank of Korea Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank will also expand the supply of cash reserves
and the issuance of bank notes and payment reserves to gradually
lower market interest rates, said Kwon Jung-hyun, spokesman for
the bank.
</P>
<P>
The central bank supplied reserve money totaling 19.8 trillion
won (15.8 billion U.S. dollars) last month.
</P>
<P>
The declining pace of the nation's production and domestic
demand has slowed down and the credit crunch eased as a result of
the steady down-sliding market interest rates.
</P>
<P>
However, the overall South Korean economy still shows no sign
of recovery.
</P>
<P>
That is why the bank intends to make a stronger push to lower
call rates through "open market operations," a mechanism to
control liquidity by purchasing or selling state and public bonds,
while making an effort to stabilize the foreign exchange market,
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The bank's efforts to pull down market interest rates,
including call rates, are designed to help domestic enterprises
reduce their heavy financial burdens and further stabilize the
exchange rate of the South Korean won against the U.S. dollar,
said the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
