<HEADLINE> China, a Source of Stability in Asia: WB Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A World Bank Principal
Economist said here Thursday that China has been a source of great
stability in Asia ever since the financial crisis started in the
region in July last year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on the World Bank Global
Economic Prospects of 1998/99, which was released Thursday in
Washington, Dipak Dasgupta, lead author of the report, said that
China has pursued policies that have helped maintain stability in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The growth of China's economy may be slowed down due to various
factors including the serious flood in the country this year and
the slow-down of its domestic consumption growth.
</P>
<P>
However, China can still achieve more than a 7-percent growth
this year and it will remain about that level in 1999, Dasgupta
said. So China is one of the largest countries in the region which
is enjoying a very strong growth, he added.
</P>
<P>
During the conference held Thursday afternoon at the Foreign
Correspondents Club of Hong Kong, Dasgupta said that China's
growth obviously has a major influence over Hong Kong's economy.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been forced to defend itself during the crisis
but it is also a source of great stability in this region, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
