<HEADLINE> Pakistan, India Initial Agreement on Bus Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and India Thursday
initialed an agreement on opening bus service between New Delhi
and Lahore, a major city in eastern Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was worked out during the two-day talks here
attended by a six-member Indian delegation led by R.B Bhati, Joint
Secretary of Surface Transport Ministry, and a 10-member Pakistani
team led by Ashraf Hayat, Joint Secretary of the Communications
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of discussions, "an agreement and a protocol
providing a framework and operational mechanism for opening bus
service between eastern Pakistan and the Indian capital," said a
joint statement issued here Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
"Follow-up action will be taken for signing of the agreement by
the two governments. The bus service, is expected to commence by
the middle of January 1999," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and Indian Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee agreed to open the bus service during their
meeting in the U.N. General Assembly in New York in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
