<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economy Up 2.8 Percent in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Germany's economy showed robust
growth in the third quarter, rising by 2.8 percent on an annual
basis and up 0.9 percent over the second quarter, the German
Federal Statistics Office announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The office's report also said the gain in eastern Germany was
1.7 percent lower than that of western Germany's 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the gain to strong private consumption
and domestic demand, while noting that exports, the traditional
pillar of the German economy, have played a relatively weaker role.
</P>
<P>
Private consumption rose by 2.2 percent in the third quarter,
faster than the average rise in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
Exports in the third quarter went up by 3.1 percent on an
annual basis, a slowdown from the eight percent rise in the first
half of 1998. Meanwhile imports were up by 3.5 percent, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Further significant figures in the report concerned
employment. The number of jobholders in western Germany shot up by
90,000 or 0.3 percent and those in eastern German were up by
26,000 or 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate still remains high at an average 10.7
percent for the quarter, but slightly below the 11.3 percent in
the spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
