<HEADLINE> Malaysia Applies 3b U.S. Dollars in Loans from WB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has submitted
applications to the World Bank for loans totaling 3 billion U.S.
dollars this year, Second Finance Minister Mustapa Mohamed said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The applications were made in stages, in May for 300 million
U.S. dollars, in June for another 700 million U.S. dollars and in
July for 2 billion U.S. dollars, he told reporters at Parliament
lobby here, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia received in June the 300 million U.S. dollars applied
in May to overcome the economic downturn for providing micro
credit and for the implementation of poverty eradication program,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank would need more time to process the loan
applications submitted in June and July this year as the loans
involved various ministries, sectors and projects.
</P>
<P>
He said the loans sought this year were mostly for the
construction of low-cost houses, the agricultural sector,
infrastructures, land transport, education and the economic
sector.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank had sent six missions last month to
gather facts and made assessments before making recommendations to
its board of directors. 
</P>
