the People's Consultative Assembly/House of Representatives
(MPR/DPR) have agreed to hold the general election on June 7,
1999, House Speaker Harmoko said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Referring to the people's aspiration, the general election --
as part of the reform agenda on political affairs -- is scheduled
to be held on June 7 next year, while the first phase of the
general session of the MPR will be held on August 29," Harmoko
told reporters after a meeting with the President B.J. Habibie at
the legislative assembly building.
</P>
<P>
The election was previously set in May 1999 and the MPR's
general assembly in December in the same year.
</P>
<P>
"The holding of the general session of the MPR in 1999
constitutes an effort to form a new government based on the
results of the general election," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the general election and the MPR's general session,
Harmoko also explained the DPR's commitment to following up the
implementation of the MPR decrees adopted during the body's
special session last month.
</P>
<P>
The president, according to Harmoko, is committed to
implementing the MPR Decree which includes a probe into the
alleged hidden wealth of former president Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
He said the legislative body will take proactive steps to
follow up these MPR decrees with laws, either in the economic,
political or legal fields. 
</P>
