<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Closely Watches U.S.-India Nuclear Talks: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has delinked its
position on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) from India
but it is closely following the Indian negotiations with the
United States on the issue, Minister of State for Foreign Affairs
Siddique Kanju said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Following the tests (by Pakistan), we do not consider it
necessary to link our position on the CTBT with India,
nevertheless, we are closely following the Indian negotiations
with the United States on this issue," he said while addressing
the International Conference on Peace and Security in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan is ready to adhere to the CTBT provided the
atmosphere of coercion and pressure is removed.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan remains committed not to exporting sensitive
technology to a third country or entity," he said. "This is a
responsible policy adopted for over two decades. We are ready to
further tighten our controls where necessary."
</P>
<P>
Kanju said Pakistan has agreed to the commencement of
negotiations in the Conference on Disarmament regarding the
conclusion of a Fissile Material Cut off Treaty (FMCT).
</P>
<P>
He said that the nuclearization of South Asia cannot be
reversed. "Nuclear deterrence is now fundamental to Pakistan's
security."
</P>
<P>
Indeed, with wide conventional disparity, he said, Pakistan's
reliance on a nuclear deterrence is imperative.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he said, there is an urgent need for both
Pakistan and India to promote understanding and stability in order
to avoid nuclear arms race and conflict in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan had already acted with restraint, declared a
unilateral moratorium on testing and offered India a regional test
ban treaty."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's dialogue with the United States, he said, on nuclear
and security issues and with India on peace and security is
governed by "both our fundamental security considerations and our
sensitivity to international non-proliferation concerns."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, has pursued the goal of nuclear non-
proliferation as it has realized that a nuclear race in South Asia
will have far-reaching consequences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Tycoons Asked to Donate Personal Wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The bosses of South Korean
family-owned conglomerates, or chaebols, will be asked to donate
their personal wealth to help reduce the debts of their business
groups, said a top presidential advisor on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The nation's top five chaebols -- Samsung, Hyundai, Daewoo, LG
and SK -- will sign an agreement with their creditor banks before
December 15 to specify ways of reducing their debts, said Kang
Bong-kyun, the top presidential advisor on economic affairs.
</P>
<P>
In their debt reduction plans, the chaebol bosses must make
clear how much of their personal wealth, including real estate,
stocks and cash, will be used and how much foreign capital they
will attract, said Kang.
</P>
<P>
Kang also said the South Korean government has been monitoring
whether the chaebols bosses have been abiding by their earlier
commitments to put their personal wealth back into their business
empires.
</P>
<P>
Under the commitment of "self-rescue efforts," creditor banks
will convert part of their debts into equity while the
conglomerates must shut down their unprofitable subsidiaries and
sell off real estate and stocks to improve the financial situation.
</P>
<P>
Unless the chaebols comply with the debt reduction plans they
sign with their creditor banks, they will be denied access to
bank credit, Kang said.
</P>
<P>
The top five chaebols are now burdened with debts of totaling
160 trillion won (130 billion U.S dollars). The ratio of debt to
equity ranges from 370-570 percent, much higher than the 85-150
percent recorded by their counterparts in Japan and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The five had previously promised to attract foreign capital of
29 billion U.S. dollars, of which only 16 percent has actually
flowed in. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Ranks 10th Among World Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- China was the tenth largest
exporters in world merchandise trade in 1997 with 182.7 billion
U.S. dollars, 21 percent more than that in 1996 when China was the
11th, according to the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
China remained the 12th importer in world merchandise trade in
1997 with 142.4 billion dollars, three percent more than that of
the previous year, said the WTO in its 1998 annual report
published here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In world commercial services trade, China was the 16th exporter
(24.5 billion dollars) and the 10th importer (30.1 billion
dollars) in the year. The growth rates of 19 percent and 34
percent were both the second highest among 25 leading world
exporters and importers.
</P>
<P>
The ten leading exporters in world merchandise trade in 1997
were the United States (688.7 billion); Germany (511.7 billion);
Japan (421.0 billion); France (289.5 billion); the United Kingdom
(281.5 billion); Italy (238.2 billion); Canada (214.4 billion);
the Netherlands (193.8 billion); Hong Kong, China (188.2 billion)
and China (182.7 billion).
</P>
<P>
The ten leading importers in world merchandise trade were the
United States (899.0 billion); Germany (441.5 billion); Japan
(338.8 billion); the United Kingdom (308.2 billion); France (268.4
billion); Hong Kong, China (213.3 billion); Italy (208.1 billion);
Canada (201.0 billion); the Netherlands (177.2 billion) and
Belgium-Luxembourg (155.8 billion).
</P>
<P>
The ten leading exporters in world trade in commercial services
were the United States (229.9 billion); the United Kingdom (85.5
billion); France (80.3 billion); Germany (75.4 billion); Italy
(71.7 billion); Japan (68.1 billion); the Netherlands (48.5
billion); Spain (43.6 billion); Hong Kong, China (37.3 billion)
and Belgium-Luxembourg (34.0 billion).
</P>
<P>
The ten leading importers in world trade in commercial services
were the United States (150.1 billion), Japan (122.1 billion),
Germany (120.1 billion), Italy (70.1 billion), the United Kingdom
(68.6 billion), France (62.1 billion), the Netherlands (43.8
billion), Canada (35.9 billion), Belgium-Luxembourg (32.1 billion)
and China (30.1 billion). 
</P>
</TEXT>
