<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Sprinter Jayasinghe to Run in Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- World women's 200 meters silver
medalist Susanthika Jayasinghe of Sri Lanka will come for the
Asian Games on Saturday and run in four events, a top official of
the Sri Lankan delegation said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Maiya Gunasekera, Chef de Mission of the Sri Lankan delegation,
said the continent's most controversial track star Jayasinghe has
not been affected by the doping scandal and is in a superb form.
</P>
<P>
"She has been totally cleared of the doping offence," said
Gunasekera, who headed the country's delegation to arrive at the
Bangkok international airport this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"She is in a good form and is ready to run. I believe she will
win all the gold medals from the four events," he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that Jayasinghe will arrive here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"She is a strong-willed person," Gunasekera said. "The doping
case failed to cast a shadow over her, and she has been training
very hard."
</P>
<P>
Jayasinghe, 23, won the 200 meters silver medal at the World
Championships in Athens in 1997 with a time of 22.39, posing the
main hurdle in the Asian Games against China's sprint star Li
Xuemei, who holds women's 100 and 200 meters Asian records.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan was first temporarily suspended from
participating in all international events after she failed a
random drug test conducted by the world's track and field
governing body IAAF in April.
</P>
<P>
She was then cleared of the charges in August by the Asian
Athletics Association after a three-member committee appointed to
study the issue ruled not guilty for her.
</P>
<P>
But IAAF announced last month that her doping case did not end
and will be submitted to the arbitration panel.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Jayasinghe is eventually allowed to run in the Asian Games
pending the ruling from the arbitration panel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
