<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Trade Surplus Down to 28 billion Dollars in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's trade surplus is
expected to fall to 28 billion U.S. dollars in 1999 from an
estimated 40 billion this year due to a rise of imports, the Korea
International Trade Association said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a report on the 1999 trade outlook, the association said
increased export of electronics products and automobiles will
depend on demand from developing countries and could be offset by
a slowdown of the U.S. economy, pushing up export volume by a mere
0.4 percent to 133 billion dollars next year.
</P>
<P>
The heavy-industry export is expected to rise 2.4 percent while
light-industry one will drop 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, import is due to jump 13.5 percent to 105 billion
dollars, reflecting a reduction in inventories.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of another foreign currency crisis is low
because of current-account surplus and steady inflow of foreign
investment capital, said the association.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the South Korean won is expected to make a stable
movement at the level 1.300 against the U.S. dollar, added the
association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
