<HEADLINE> China Gives Top Priority to Anti-Doping at Asiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- China gives top priority to
ensuring a drug-free Asian Games, a Chinese senior sports official
said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Li Furong, vice president of Chinese Olympic Committee, said
upon his arrival at Bangkok international airport:"We treat it as
a major issue to make sure that there will be no Chinese athletes
test positive in the upcoming Asian Games."
</P>
<P>
"In preparing for the games, we strengthened doping control and
conducted a total of 2,412 from January to October this year, " he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Nine athletes were caught in the tests," he said. "All of them
have been banned from any international competitions according to
anti-doping rules.
</P>
<P>
Eleven Chinese athletes tested positive at the Hiroshima Asian
Games four years ago. 
</P>
