<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Predicts Lower Global Trade Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The growth rate of world
merchandise exports for 1998 is expected to be between four and
five percent, less than half of that in 1997, said the World Trade
Organization (WTO) here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The sharper than projected deceleration of global output and
trade in 1998 is largely attributable to the underestimation of
the recession in Japan and the deeper and more widespread
repercussions of the financial crisis in East Asian countries,"
said the WTO in its 1998 annual report.
</P>
<P>
The East Asian financial crisis which began in the latter half
of 1997, and the severity of the down turn in the Japanese economy
in 1998, together with slower growth in the United Kingdom and
Latin America led to reduced global economic activity.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, the downward tendency was somewhat
mitigated by increased momentum in continental West Europe.
</P>
<P>
The slump in Asia's growth contributed significantly to
depressed commodity markets, with oil prices and non-fuel
commodity prices falling by about 30 percent and 15 percent
respectively on an annual average basis.
</P>
<P>
"This year will be the third in a row with a decrease in the
dollar prices of internationally traded goods," said the
report. "Average prices for total merchandise exports are falling
back to the level of 1991, the lowest in the 1990s."
</P>
<P>
Expectations regarding global trade growth in 1999 have been
lowered in recent months, said the WTO. Most forecasters regard a
moderate acceleration in volume growth compared to 1998 as the
most likely scenario.
</P>
<P>
In value terms, the WTO predicted that the recovery should be
more pronounced as price declines for primary commodities are
partly reversed and the dollar is not expected to strengthen.
</P>
<P>
"The actual outcome will depend in large measure on
developments in international capital markets, the rate of
recovery in Asia and in particular Japan, and the sustainability
of growth momentum in Western Europe and North America," it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Scheme Offers More loans to HK Home Buyers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Mortgage
Corporation (HKMC) announced here Thursday that it is expected to
launch a new guarantee scheme at Spring next year to enable local
home buyers to obtain a mortgage up to 85 percent of the value of
the property.
</P>
<P>
Peter Pang, chief executive officer of the HKMC, announced
Thursday that the Board of Directors of the HKMC has given its
approval in principle for the corporation to partner with mortgage
insurers to launch a mortgage guarantee scheme which will enable
home buyers to secure mortgage loans up to 85 percent
loan-to-valuation (LTV) ratio.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed scheme, the HKMC will provide a guarantee at
a fee to the lending bank (which has to be an approved seller of
the HKMC) for an amount up to 15 percent of the value of the
property to enable the bank to extend the mortgage loan up to 85
percent of LTV ratio from the existing 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
The HKMC will fully hedge the exposure of the guarantee by
taking out an insurance of equal amount with a mortgage insurer,
Pang said.
</P>
<P>
Donald Tsang, financial secretary of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) and chairman of the HKMC, described
this scheme as a win-win solution for all parties -- home buyers,
banks, HKMC and the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement will also help improve the liquidity in the
property market, particularly in respect of secondary property
transactions, Tsang said. The HKMC is a wholly-owned corporation
of the HKSAR government through the exchange fund.
</P>
<P>
"With the approval of the board, we will conduct detailed
negotiations with the mortgage insurers on the terms of the
back-to-back mortgage insurance and seek formal authorization as
an authorized insurer under the Insurance Companies Ordinance,"
Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
If everything goes well, the product is expected to be launched
in the first quarter of 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dominic Wong, secretary for housing of the SAR, welcomed the
HKMC announcement, saying that the proposed arrangement for using
mortgage insurance to enable banks to lend beyond the 70 percent
mortgage ceiling without increasing additional risk will have
positive impact on the property market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
