<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Powerful China Contigent Arrives at Bangkok for Gold Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BNAGKOK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Some four hundred sports
officials and athletes of the Chinense Asiad delegation arrived
here Thursday afternoon for the 13th Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
The Asian sports giant, which collected 137 gold medals four
years ago at Hiroshima, sent the sports delegation in two
chartered plane from Guangzhou and Beijing respectively, with 207
in the first and 193 in the second.
</P>
<P>
"Ninty percent of the Chinese delegation has been in Bangkok,"
Li Furong, deputy Chef de Mission of the Chinese delegation, said
upon his arrival at the Bangkok international airport.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation for the 13th Asian Games consists of 822
athletes and officials. They will take part in 32 out of 36
events at the games.
</P>
<P>
Among the 400 athletes who arrived here on Thursday are teams
of diving, swimming, basketball, judo, volleyball, canoeing,
rowing, fencing, shooting and weightlifting, which are believed to
contribute most of China's gold medals in the Games.
</P>
<P>
The all-conquoring table tennis as well as badminton teams will
get here later.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Weimin, Chef de Mission of the Chinese delegation, said he
was confident that Chinese athletes would take lion's share of
gold medals at the games.
</P>
<P>
"I think China can win over 100 gold medals," said Yuan Weimin.
"But I'm not sure whether we can win more or less than the 137 we
got at the Hiroshima Games."
</P>
<P>
Yuan said China aims higher than just winning gold medals:"I
cannot say it is good or bad to win more than 137 gold medals. We
hope that through the Asian Games, we can find some young talents
with potential to win honor at the 2000 Olympic Games and other
world competitions."
</P>
<P>
Yuan said that main part of the Chinese delegation was formed
by young athletes since a lot of veterans have retired after the
Chinese Eighth National Games last year.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the veteran athletes can put on world-class performance
instead of just winning gold medals," Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
Yuan also said that the performance of Chinese athletes at the
Asian Games was closely related to China's bid for the 2008
Olympic Games, though gold medals was just one side of their
efforts.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot only depend on the gold medals and results of the
athletes to bid for the Olympics," he said. "But the reason we
submitted our bid right before the Asian Games was to say we are
contributing greatly for the Olympic movement."  
</P>
</TEXT>
