<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Business Community Expects Greater Cooperation with Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A business leader in Hong
Kong expressed the hope Thursday that greater cooperation between
Hong Kong and Japan's business communities will help ease the
economic adjustment of the two economies.
</P>
<P>
"In the economic adjustment process both of our economies are
currently going through, greater cooperation between our two
business communities can make this process easier," said
Dr. Raymond Chien, chairman of the Hong Kong/Japan Business
Cooperation Committee.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the 21st Session of HK/Japan and Japan/HK
Business Cooperation Committees, to be held in Tokyo Friday, Chien
said the prime objective of this meeting is "to create deeper
mutual understanding between our two business communities of the
hurdles we are each facing."
</P>
<P>
The committees, established in 1979, meet in Japan and Hong
Kong in alternate years to review the latest business development
and discuss economic and trade issues that affect the two
economies.
</P>
<P>
At the 21st session the committees will discuss the
implications of Japan's reform program, Hong Kong's program for
boosting its economic competitiveness, and the opportunities for
business partnership that will open up as the Asian economies
begin to recover.
</P>
<P>
Japan is Hong Kong's third largest export market and second
largest source of imports. Japan is also the largest investor in
Hong Kong's manufacturing sector and the fourth largest investor
in the non-manufacturing sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
