<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Dive on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Share prices took a hit on
Singapore Stock Market Thursday after a limp rebound Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) shed 40.16 points to
close at 1,343.43 points, off their intra-day lows with blue chips
and banks leading the fall.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover increased to 228.54 million units valued at
385.90 million Singapore dollars (234.68 million U.S. dollars).
Decliners edged out advancers by 259 to 24 while 137 counters
remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
ST Engg topped the actives chart of the day with a turnover of
21.77 million units. Van DH was the second most heavily traded
stock with 17.65 million shares done. Wing T was next with 7.86
million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
NatElect led the ascent of the day with a 14-cent rise to 3.50
Singapore dollars. RothmansI gained 10 cents to end at 9.15
Singapore dollars. Metalock moved up five cents to finish at 0.50
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 led the descent of the day as it
dropped 110 cents to 27.30 Singapore dollars. SPH sank 90 cents to
16.60 Singapore dollars. SPH 100 retreated 70 cents to end at
16.70 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said share prices were weakened as institutions
unloaded index-linked blue chips on concerns of global job losses
from the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the dampened market sentiment to the slump in
regional bourses and the fall on Wall Street Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that investors remained on the sidelines as
there was no fresh factors which could spur the market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
