<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Pros Set Eyes on Asiad Hoop Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- As Asia's 13th quadrennial
sporting gala is two days away, the men's basketball competition
will unveil the mask of an all-pro Philippine Centennial team,
which aims to end the country's hoop gold drought since 1974.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines reapt four consecutive gold medals in the first
Asian games from 1951 to 1962 and regained the title in the 1974
Tehran Games.
</P>
<P>
But the basketball crazy islanders have never repeated the
glory since launching their professional league PBA in 1975 when
the country was then represented by amateurs in international
meets.
</P>
<P>
The best result the Filipinos have attained was a silver medal
at the Beijing Games by a hastily-shuffled PBA All-Star team in
1990.
</P>
<P>
After a hiatus of eight years, the Philippines vows to fight to
win the gold in the Bangkok Games by fielding in their best pro
cagers in the Centennial team as the country celebrated its 100th
anniversary of freedom from Spanish domination in June.
</P>
<P>
The mission would be dire tough for the Filipinos as they know
clearly that three-time defending champion China and the
newly-crowned Asian championship winner South Korea were on their
ways to the top of the podium.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the Filipinos are not to surrender without fight but to
whet their weapons for tough battles from both China and South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Centennial team, led by Manila-based American
coach Tim Cone, went to the United States for a 22-day tour
against the collegiate teams one month before the Bangkok Games.
</P>
<P>
"The Philippines' biggest problems will definitely come from
China and South Korea," admitted Cone before leaving for the US
trip. "We've got to overachieve to beat China."
</P>
<P>
"Aside from China and South Korea, the Philippines is also
closely watching teams from Japan, Kazakhstan and Kyrgystan," said
Cone.
</P>
<P>
The basketball competition will start from December 8 through
19 with more than 16 teams competing in the last Asian Games of
the century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
