<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Discovers Debt Buy-back Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is
investigating a 2.5 billion-Dollar debt buy-back fraud involving
two former ministers and a member of the family of late Head of
State General Sani Abacha, media reports here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Press Secretary to the Head of State, Malam Mohammed
Haruna, disclosed in Nigerian capital Abuja Wednesday that the
three people involved had already made statements to the police.
</P>
<P>
He said that the money was the debt owed by the Nigerian
government to a Russian company handling the Ajaokuta Steel
Company in the country.
</P>
<P>
Haruna noted that some ministers and a member of the Abacha
family had an interest in the debt.
</P>
<P>
They went abroad and registered a company which had reached an
agreement with the Russian company to buy back the 2.5
billion-Dollar debt for 500 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
They paid the Russian company off with the 500 million Dollars
and shared two billion Dollars which is the difference between
what Nigeria owed and what they paid, said Haruna, adding that
that is what is being investigated.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that an additional 130 million Naira (about
1.5 million Dollars) had been identified under the votes of the
former National Security Adviser Alhaji Ismaila Gwarzo.
</P>
<P>
The money is part of the 64 billion Naira (about 744 million
Dollars) earlier recovered from the family of the late General
Abacha, he added.
</P>
<P>
Investigations have reached advanced stage and the money will
soon be recovered, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
