<HEADLINE> Nigeria Airways to Open Flight to S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- An aviation official has
confirmed that the Nigeria Airways would commence its scheduled
flight operations to Johannesburg next week, The Post Express
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Jani Ibrahim, Chief Executive of Nigeria Airways
Limited, was quoted as saying that arrangements had reached
advanced stage to ensure smooth operations on the virgin route.
</P>
<P>
All flights to South Africa will be routed through Nnamdi
Zikiwe International Airport in capital Abuja instead of the
Murtala Muhammed International Airport in Lagos, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, services on the route will be conducted in a
leased DC-10 aircraft, probably from Europe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a statement issued in Lagos by the South African
Airways said that direct flights between South Africa and Nigeria
would start on December 3 using a Boeing 767 airplane.
</P>
<P>
Although there is no bilateral air service agreement between
the two countries, a memorandum of understanding signed by them
allows for two flights on every Monday and Thursday by the South
African Airways.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources here believe that with direct links between
Lagos and Johannesburg, commercial activities and cultural
interactions will receive a boost and cement the existing cordial
relationship between the two giant African nations.
</P>
<P>
There have been several efforts to open direct air link
between Nigeria and South Africa since the dismantling of
apartheid in the gold-rich country.
</P>
<P>
Political problems and other issues have prevented the
much-expected direct flights from taking off.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two African countries worsened and
reached its lowest ebb during the regime of the late General Sani
Abacha who, in spite of overtures from President Nelson Mandela,
went on to kill Ken Saro-Wiwa, an acclaimed environmentalist, and
his eight Ogoni kinsmen in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
