<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down 1.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Profit-taking and negative
offshore influences dragged the Australian share market almost
1.5 percent lower Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index slipped 40.7 points to
2,720.3.
</P>
<P>
"There have been negative influences from offshore ... and
there's been a bit of profit taking, especially in the banks,"
said Wilson HTM dealer Ben Skubris.
</P>
<P>
On Australian equities markets, the all industrials index
tumbled 62.6 points to 4,848.2, while the resources index
retreated 25 points to 988.0.
</P>
<P>
Australia's resources giant BHP lost 42.1 cents to 12.00
Australian dollars, dragging the resources sector down.
Diversified miner Rio Tinto dropped 35.9 cents to 19.65
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, profit-taking eroded Thursday's interest
cut-related gains, with the banking index diving 113.2 points to
6,085.9.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank of Australia tumbled 45.3 cents to 21.776
Australian dollars, Westpac bank and National Australia Bank both
offloaded 30 cents to 9.98 Australian dollars and 23.50 Australian
dollars respectively, and ANZ bank slid 27 cents to 10.18
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index retreated 17.8 points to 1,104.3 on weaker gold
prices.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney Thursday afternoon was
293.25 U.S. dollars an ounce, compared to Wednesday's close of
294.25 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 315.63 million worth 634.13 million U.S.
dollars, with falling stocks outnumbering rising stocks 675 to 458
and 411 stocks steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
