<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes One U.S. Cent Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar shed
more than one U.S. cent Thursday as it succumbed to pressure from
poor commodities prices and overseas fall-out from Wednesday's
Reserve Bank of Australia rate cut.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed Thursday at 62.60 U.S. cents from 63.68
U.S. cents previously, after spending the day between 62.38 and
63.02 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
A major factor in the performance was falling commodity prices,
with the Commodity Research Bureau Index (CRB) down by 0.84 at
195.99.
</P>
<P>
The CRB is an index of 21 U.S. futures markets and although it
is not weighted to Australia's exports, traders follow it as an
indicator for the commodity price-sensitive Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's announcement by the Reserve Bank of Australia to
reduce the cash rate to 4.75 percent from 5.00 percent also saw
market participants sell.
</P>
<P>
On the cross rates Thursday, the Australian dollar was buying
74.75 Japanese yen from 77.53 yen Wednesday and 1.0453 German
marks from 1.0714 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
