<HEADLINE> Philippine President Orders Probe of Orphanage Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Thursday inspected the ruins of a Manila orphanage and
ordered an investigation into the cause of the blaze that killed
24 children and three nannies.
</P>
<P>
Estrada expressed deep regret over the tragedy while inspecting
the ruins of the 85-year-old house settlement in Paco, Manila.
</P>
<P>
After asking about the circumstances leading to the fire, the
president invited officials running the orphanage to meet him in
the presidential palace at the soonest.
</P>
<P>
Fire officials said that 24 kids and three nannies were killed
in the fire, and eight children are still missing and feared dead.
</P>
<P>
They said that faulty wire might have caused the fire, which
started at 02:09 Thursday (18:09 GMT Wednesday) and was placed
under control after more than three hours.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers, volunteer groups and terrified parents are
still searching for the missing people from the debris of the
blaze.
</P>
<P>
The settlement house was occupied by at least 70 people,
including abandoned children, babies left by their working parents
on a day care basis and volunteers who take care of the kids,
firemen said.
</P>
<P>
The survivors were brought to the nearby parish church in Plaza
Dilao.
</P>
<P>
The corpses were transferred to a funeral home.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Jerry Barican said that Estrada is
eyeing a partnership between the government and the private sector
in rebuilding the orphanage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
