<HEADLINE> South China Lake Disappears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The disappearance of a lake has
been the subject of wide-ranging conjecture in south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, according to today's edition of
the Beijing Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
The dry rectangular lake bed located near the village of
Lianjing in Jingxi County covers 20 hectares.
</P>
<P>
The article noted that the water level dropped by 20
centimeters per day beginning on October 15, with all water
disappearing over the following eight days.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers noted that the lake thrived for over a hundred
years, with the surface area consistently remaining above 13 ha
even during severe droughts.
</P>
<P>
The actual cause is under investigation. However, the article
points out the lake formed as a result of local karst features
which created subsidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
