<HEADLINE> China Enjoys Rapid Scientific, Technological Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The past two decades have
witnessed a rapid development in China's modern science and
technology, according to Lu Yongxiang, president of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
Scientific reform has been accelerated since the Third Plenum
of the 11th Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee in
1978, said Lu. He made the remarks at a recent symposium on the
plenum which introduced the reform and opening-up policy.
</P>
<P>
Lu said the CAS has followed the guidelines outlined at the
plenum and has taken the lead by sending students and researchers
abroad to study and initiating scientific cooperation with the
United States, Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
CAS also established China's first "open laboratories" and a
special fund for natural science studies.
</P>
<P>
"The measures have provided valuable experience for
establishing a new innovation system and exploring ways to reform
the science and technology system," said Lu.
</P>
<P>
CAS plans to build itself into a center for knowledge and
innovation by the year 2010, with related efforts focusing on
strategic scientific projects and advanced international
scientific studies.
</P>
<P>
Twelve related CAS pilot projects are progressing smoothly
now.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cutting China's Longest Railway Tunnel (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A driver presses buttons in the cab, breathing air that is
pumped in by a ventilator. The hard rock is being cut to pieces
and carted out of the tunnel on narrow tracks and water used in
the cutting runs into a water-treatment pool before it is released
into the valley.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jun, senior engineer on the project, told reporters that
work on the Qinling Range tunnel started at the end of last year
and more than 6,000 meters have been covered.
</P>
<P>
The Qinling Range in the middle of China, where the tunnel is
being bored, has a 2,800 meter main peak. It forms a demarcation
line between northern and southern climates and a watershed
between the Yangtze and Yellow rivers.
</P>
<P>
Li Henian, chief engineer of the Xi'an-Ankang project, says
that several generations of Chinese have long dreamed of a tunnel
through Qinling Range, but because of the length, complex
geological structure, and possible disasters, a number of railways
had to be built around it.
</P>
<P>
So, to realize this dream and improve rail transport in
southwestern and midwestern China, the Chinese government decided
to put more than 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion US dollars) into a
railway going directly goes through the middle of Qinling
Range. The Qinling tunnel alone will cost over 2 billion yuan (240
million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
It took engineers some eight years before they hit on the
present plan, which allows the tunnel to pass through five big
faults in the shortest way, Li said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cutting China's Longest Railway Tunnel (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The tunnel will have two basically parallel single-track
tunnels, 30 m apart, and the total length of the two is just over
18 km.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the success of the tunnel, China spent a great deal
on the most sophisticated excavating equipment, including two TBMs
from Germany's Wirth, which cost 750 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for China to use TBMs. Liu Jun says that
Chinese quickly caught on to the technology.
</P>
<P>
Li Henian says that a 9,500 m-long single-end ventilation was a
major accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
The Xi'an-Ankang Railway runs from the Longhai railway
(Lanzhou-Lianyungang) in the north to the Xiangfan-Chongqing rail
line and Baoji-Chengdu rail route in the south. It is one of the
leading construction project in China's development program for
1996-2000.
</P>
<P>
When completed in 2000, it will form another north-south trunk
railway line, and the railway trip from Xi'an, the capital of
Shaanxi province, to Ankang in southern Shaanxi will be shortened
from 18 hours to about three hours.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increased Consumption to Promote Chinese Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese economists contend that
the nation can achieve economic prosperity by promoting further
development of the domestic market in answer to the turbulent
international economy.
</P>
<P>
Increasing domestic investments and consumption are playing an
increasingly important role in maintaining stable economic
development as a result of declining growth rates for both exports
and foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Li Xiaochao, deputy director of the State Statistics Bureau's
Intergrated Statistics Department, said China has reaped positive
results in efforts to invest more in fixed assets and ignite
market demand. He noted that China's economic situation
undoubtedly improve in line with related efforts.
</P>
<P>
Li admitted that Chinese enterprises and members of the general
public thus far refrained from active investments and consumption,
and noted that the government is adopting additional measures to
boost consumption.
</P>
<P>
Noted Economist Hu Angang pointed to the macro level and noted
that China is a developing country which must strengthen
development of its railway, highway, higher education and medical
care sectors.
</P>
<P>
China's accelerated urbanization, environmental protection and
ecological projects offer vast opportunities for investors, said
Hu, adding that the nation has exhibited less restraint and
greater generosity in terms of overall economic policies.
</P>
<P>
"Shortages of construction capital are longer the main obstacle
hindering economic development," according to Hu. He also noted
that the Chinese economy will be further fueled up by breaking
monopolies and encourage the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Many difficulties remain in spite the fanfare surrounding
increasing domestic demand, according to observers..
</P>
<P>
China's ongoing reform of the housing and medical care sectors
reform have led to a retrenchment in spending, and massive
layoffs have sharpened the general public's awareness of possibly
financial instability and in turn sparked increased savings.
</P>
<P>
Increased market competition has forced many companies to adopt
a strategy of less spending for product upgrades and increased
investments in other areas.
</P>
<P>
However, a broad domestic market is in place and China can
expect greater market development of the domestic which will
continue to grow the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
