<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Detains Human Rights Group Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian court has ordered the
detention of Secretary General of the Egyptian Organization for
Human Rights (EOHR) Hafez Abu Saada for receiving foreign funds
with the intention of damaging national interests.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported Thursday that Egypt's
Higher State Security Court issued the order Wednesday after
questioning him over a 25,000-U.S.-dollar check offered to the
group by the British embassy in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Under the order, Abu Saada will be held in custody for 15 days
as part of the investigation, a judicial official said.
</P>
<P>
He was accused of accepting foreign funds without official
approval in advance and spreading allegations that have
jeopardized the national interests, the official said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the EOHR secretary general was jailed
since its founding in 1985. Abu Saada would face seven to 15 years
of hard labor if convicted, according to judicial sources.
</P>
<P>
The private Al Usbou weekly has reported that EOHR received the
check offered by the British Parliament's Human Rights Committee
via the British embassy after it released a statement alleging
police brutality against Copts in southern Egypt. The weekly
denounced the organization of committing treason.
</P>
<P>
Al Usbou Editor-in Chief Mustafa Bakri has also displayed a
copy of the check and another EOHR statement on the incident in
Suhag Governorate's Kosheh village, where 70 percent of its 35,000
residents are Christian Copts.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette reported on November 1 that EOHR had
issued a statement that more than 1,000 Copts were rounded up by
the security forces who were investigating the killing of two
Copts.
</P>
<P>
Based on the allegations, Britain's Sunday Telegraph newspaper
said: "Egyptian Christians have been subjected to horrific
crucification rituals, raped and tortured by the security forces
during a crackdown on the ancient Coptic community."
</P>
<P>
Egypt's parliament, social groups and celebrities have
denounced the story of the British newspaper as a fabrication
aimed at defaming Egypt where Muslims and Christians have been
co-existing in peace for more than 14 centuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
