<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Severino: Hanoi Summit to Push for Early Recovery of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
Association of Southeast Asian nations (ASEAN) Rodolfo Severino
Jr. has said that the Sixth ASEAN Summit scheduled in Hanoi,
Vietnam, will come up with concrete measures to push for the early
recovery of ASEAN economies.
</P>
<P>
Severino made the statement Wednesday at the Conference on the
Economic Prospects and the Environment in Asia held in Kuala
Lumpur, a media release issued here Thursday by the ASEAN
Secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN leaders, Severino said, will issue a mandate for a
more rapid integration of markets in goods and services and
liberalization of trade and investment regimes to further improve
the business climate of the region.
</P>
<P>
He said the ASEAN leaders are expected to take strong steps to
hasten the ASEAN Free Trade Area establishment and to draw
investments into ASEAN. An agreement on facilitating goods in
transit is expected to be signed, he said, adding that these and
other economic measures to be undertaken in the next three to six
years will be on the agenda of the summit to ensure ASEAN's
competitiveness in the global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general said the Hanoi Summit to be held on
December 15-16 promises to be productive "Summit of Concrete
Measures".
</P>
<P>
He also said ASEAN leaders will be meeting with those of China,
Japan and South Korea. "The meetings with all three Northeast
Asian leaders and with each of them in turn will be of great
importance to the future of our region."
</P>
<P>
"China is a rising force in the regional and the global
economy; Japan is the world's second economic power, Asia's
leading economy and ASEAN's leading economic partner; South Korea
is a victim of the crisis, and is cooperating with ASEAN in
dealing with it", he explained.
</P>
<P>
Severino said there is now a growing confidence in ASEAN among
multinationals and investors and cited the following three
conditions:
</P>
<P>
The first, he said, is that the factors that made three decades
of rapid growth possible remain in place in ASEAN. These are
healthy budgets, high savings rates, natural resources, relatively
good infrastructure, and an educated, skilled, motivated and
mobile labor force.
</P>
<P>
The second is that ASEAN members are dealing forcefully with
the ravages of the crisis, each in its own way -- "a clean-up of
the banking and financial system, capital infusion, expansionary
measures, belt-tightening. Some are doing it in partnership with
the International Monetary Fund (IMF), others on their own.
</P>
<P>
These efforts are starting to show results, he said, adding
that "currencies are being stabilized, inflation is coming under
control, and interest rates are going down." There are guarded
forecasts of the beginning of a recovery sometime next year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The third, he said, is that the international community seems
to be finally getting itself together in grappling with what has
become a global problem.
</P>
<P>
"Now is the time for business people who are alert to
opportunities to take a close look at ASEAN," Severino said.
"ASEAN's market of 500 million people is integrating and further
opening up to trade and investment. The economic reforms now
taking place will make ASEAN a better place in which to do
business."
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Malaysia, Indonesia, the Philippines,
Laos, Myanmar, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
