<HEADLINE> Japan's Real GDP Drops by 0.7 Percent in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Japan's gross domestic product
(GDP) in the third quarter of this year shrank by a preliminary
0.7 percent from the previous quarter in real terms, or an
annualized decline of 2.6 percent, the Economic Planning Agency
(EPA) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The contraction marks the fourth consecutive quarterly fall. It
is the first time that Japan's GDP has declined for four straight
quarters since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Private consumption, which accounts for some 60 percent of the
GDP aggregate, fell by 0.3 percent, and corporate capital spending,
another engine for growth, declined by 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Housing investment fell by 6.2 percent, while public investment
increased by 3.6 percent, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
EPA Director General Taichi Sakaiya told a press conference it
may be difficult for Japan to attain the government-set economic
forecast of 1.8 percent contraction for fiscal 1998 ending next
March 31.
</P>
<P>
GDP measures the value of goods and services produced within a
nation. Real GDP figures are adjusted for inflation and seasonal
variations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
