<HEADLINE> Australia Criticizes New Zealand Over Frigate Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer Thursday criticized neighbor New Zealand for its
refusal to purchase another Australian-built frigate, warning the
country risked losing its relevance to the region.
</P>
<P>
But visiting New Zealand Foreign Minister Don McKinnon said
Thursday his country had swapped the frigate for a squadron of
fighter planes after getting a good deal from the United States.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand decided earlier this week not to purchase a third
ANZAC frigate for just under 300 million U.S. dollars, but instead
to spend the money on improving its army, and purchasing 28 F-16
fighter jets offered by the United States at a bargain basement
price.
</P>
<P>
Downer said Australia was disappointed at New Zealand's
decision to only buy two ANZAC frigates and added that it was
important the country didn't retreat from the region.
</P>
<P>
"The last thing we want to see is a New Zealand that just walks
away from its own region," Downer was quoted by the Australian
Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We would have liked to see them go down the path of choosing
the third ship, the third ANZAC frigate, and we will just continue
to put that case to them," he said.
</P>
<P>
McKinnon, who met Downer in Canberra Thursday, said he
understood Australia's disappointment but his government could not
afford both the frigate and the fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly we were offered a deal on fighter aircraft that my
colleague the defense minister said could not have been bettered
by Santa Claus," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Downer said Australia had also offered New Zealand a generous
deal on the third frigate, but McKinnon said the United States'
offer was extraordinary and could not be ignored.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the 28 jets will cost New Zealand around
360 million U.S. dollars over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The jets were ordered by Pakistan, but canceled by the U.S.
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
