<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Headway in China's Good Neighborly Diplomacy This Year (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua Writers Li Shijia and Yang Guoqiang
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- From the heat of Malaysia to
the snows of Russia and the maple trees of Japan, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin was busy in November during a two-week visit
to the three nations, an indication of China's interest in
solidifying its good-neighborly ties for the next century.
</P>
<P>
The visit resulted in an APEC declaration in Kuala Lumpur,
Sino-Russian "no-tie" talks in Moscow, and a Sino-Japanese joint
declaration in Tokyo, as well as a Sino-ROK joint statement in
Beijing, making this good-neighborly diplomacy a cornerstone of
the country's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
With a series of high-level visits with Russia, Japan, the
Republic of Korea, Pakistan, and Viet Nam, and the Sixth APEC
Informal Leadership Meeting, China has had substantial success in
solving problems left over from the past, dealing with border
issues, and promoting bilateral and regional economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In Jiang's Russia trip, a declaration on the border issue was
signed, with eastern and western sections of the border accurately
marked for the first time to guarantee the Sino-Russian strategic
partnership.
</P>
<P>
During the Japan visit, the two sides issued a joint
declaration to build a friendly and cooperative partnership
devoted to peace and development.
</P>
<P>
President Kim Dae-jung's mid-November China trip resulted in a
framework and an orientation for a cooperative partnership for the
next century.
</P>
<P>
In October, Viet Nam's Prime Minister Phan Van Khai reaffirmed
in Beijing to strengthen trade cooperation with China, and to sign
the land border treaty before the year 2000 and to finish the
demarcation of the Beibu Gulf by then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
