<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Set to Develop Small Offshore Oil Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Two offshore oilfields in the
western part of China's Bohai Sea started production today,
signaling completion of the first-phase project for a joint
development program of small to medium-sized oilfields in the area.
</P>
<P>
Lin Shaodong, president of the China's Offshore Oil Bohai Corp
(COOBC), said the first phase project included the development of two
offshore oilfields and an onshore oil and gas processing terminal.
</P>
<P>
The Qikou 18-1 and Qikou 17-1 oilfields are respectively 46 and
58 km from Tanggu Port in Tianjin, a major industrial city in
north China. The oilfields will provide the city with a daily gas
supply of 300,000 cu.m. and an annual oil supply of 500,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Bohai Sea has abundant oil and gas reserves, including a
large group of small and medium-sized oil and gas structures,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that joint development of related oil fields
represents an important step for increasing the country's offshore
oil production.
</P>
<P>
Lin said that the joint development of small and medium-sized
oilfields in the giant Bohai Oilfield will raise its annual oil
production to over 10 million tons by the year 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
