<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo on Yen's Appreciation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled across the
board in Tokyo on Thursday due mainly to the yen's rise against
the U.S. dollar and the overnight fall on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 289.54 points, or 1.93
percent, from Wednesday's close to finish at 14,697.08.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 18.26 points or 1.59 percent to
1,128.89.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section slowed slightly to about 315
million shares, down from Wednesday's 324.10 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Toshiba Corp was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The fall does not indicate investors sold shares aggressively, but
their buying interest has declined, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Investors are concerned that the dollar's fall may bring about a
further decline in stock prices on Wall Street, he added.
</P>
<P>
Exporter shares fell as the dollar slipped below 120 yen, because a
stronger yen tends to weaken Japanese exporters' competitive edge
overseas.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers overwhelmed
gainers 1,034 to 153, with 117 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
