<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gin People: (Guangxi Ethnic Group Series) (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The household contract responsibility system was the main part
of China's rural reforms when the people's communes were
abolished. But, the rural reforms were several years late in
coming to the three peninsulas because of the war with Viet
Nam in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the hard-working Gin used the opportunity and
used the marine resources to make more money.
</P>
<P>
The Gin's ancestors migrated from Viet Nam to the peninsulas in
the 15th century. In 1990, when border trade between China and
Viet Nam resumed, the Gin on the three peninsulas became some of
its biggest beneficiaries. With no language barrier, they do a
brisk border trade with the Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
Gin people sell China-made light industrial and daily
necessities to Vietnamese businessmen from whom they purchase
marine products, timber and discarded metallic commodities. Last
year, the volume of border trade between them exceeded 100 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The government has spent 120 million yuan on 4 highways and 3
harbors since 1994, and thanks to these efforts, transportation
has improved a great deal and business is much easier, Su says.
</P>
<P>
There is 9-year compulsory education on the three
peninsulas. Before the 1980s, few Gin students made it to
university. But now members of the Gin ethnic group pass college
entrance exams or even go abroad for advanced studies.
</P>
<P>
Television sets and telephones are now found in almost all Gin
households, a quarter of which have motorcycles or
automobiles. There is one mobile phone for every five households.
</P>
<P>
"These days are the best of my life," says 81-year-old Liu
Richeng from Wutou, "children now use more money to buy snacks
than what I used to spend on meals."
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, there have been no criminal acts or
instances of public disorder among the Gin, says one local
official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheung Tze-keung Trial Is Proper: Law Professor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Prof. Chen Guangzhong, of
Southwest China University of Political Science and Law in
Chongqing and deputy head of the China Law Society, says that the
mainland has jurisdiction over the Hong Kong resident Cheung
Tze-keung and that his trial is in complete accord with the law.
</P>
<P>
Cheung Tze-keung and his 36-member gang are accused of dealing
in explosives, smuggling arms and ammunition, kidnapping people,
and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
The Intermediate People's Court of Guangzhou reached a verdict
in the trial of first instance on November 12 and the Higher
People's Court of Guangdong Province will announce the final
verdict, because some of the defendants have appealed.
</P>
<P>
Chen says that the case involves people from Hong Kong and the
mainland. The explosives and arms and ammunition charges are for
crimes committed on the mainland. The kidnapping and robberies
were committed in Hong Kong, but were plotted and prepared on the
mainland, Chen explains.
</P>
<P>
He points out that, according to Clause 1, Article 6, of
China's Criminal Law, the Criminal Law applies to all crimes
committed in the People's Republic of China's territory, except
stipulated otherwise by laws.
</P>
<P>
The people's court in the place where a crime is committed has
jurisdiction over the case, according to Article 24 of the
Criminal Procedure Law, he says, therefore mainland courts have
jurisdiction over the case of Cheung Tze-keung.
</P>
<P>
Mainland justices respect the independent judiciary of Hong
Kong, he said, and the courts of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region have jurisdiction over any crimes committed
by Hong Kong residents in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Officials Call for More Stress on Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Thai government officials have
called for special emphasis on trade liberalization to strengthen
the country's economy and protect export.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi Wednesday said
that promoting liberalization is a goal that could not be achieved
without the support of overseas capital, more sophisticated
technology and wider access to markets.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to increase trade and investment through liberalization
are aimed at protecting Thai exports from barriers and not
intended to damage local companies, Supachai said.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign support will help create more jobs with higher pay for
locals, expand foreign markets for Thai products and above all,
underline the country's economic stability in the long term," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government is trying to amend 11 contentious bills to
ensure that they support an economic recovery, he said.
</P>
<P>
Trade liberalization is seen as important by countries
worldwide. "Among ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
members of the World Trade Organization, Thailand has the most
restrictions on trade. If the government is too late to adjust
itself, the barriers will become obstacles to future trade and
slow the recovery," Supachai noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is working hard to restore the economy
and reduce reliance on foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
Plaipol Khoomsap, an academic at Thammasat University, said the
parliament should pass bills ensuring the government guarantee
that foreign capital would not take opportunities away from Thai
investors.
</P>
<P>
The government should also ensure that foreign investors do not
repatriate all their profits and, instead, they expand their
production in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"Above all, after the implementation of liberalization, foreign
countries which have trade with Thailand must lift all their
restrictions on Thai exports," he said.
</P>
<P>
Surakiat Sathirathai, a former finance minister, said the
government prefers to liberalize enterprises or businesses so that
the public would benefit. Businesses in which locals are not ready
to compete with foreigners should be under Thai control.
</P>
<P>
The government should also promise that legislation would not
be amended under foreign pressure, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Foreign Business Bill, in particular, has lots of defects
and loopholes. Its penalty chapter is quite light and gives too
much authority to commerce ministry officials," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
