<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lake Malawi's Fish Under Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The fish population in Lake
Malawi is under threat because of uncontrolled and inappropriate
fishing practices.
</P>
<P>
Malawian Environment and Fisheries Minister, Frank Mkandawire,
said Wednesday in Lilongwe that fish availability in the lake,
one of the world's largest fresh-water bodies, had declined.
</P>
<P>
The minister was quoted Thursday by The Post, a Zambian
independent newspaper, as saying the fish population had fallen
from about 15 kilograms per capita in 1970 to seven kilograms per
capita this year.
</P>
<P>
And some species had declined sharply from 6,000 tons in 1987
to 500 tons in 1996, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The situation was due mainly to increasing numbers of
fishermen who used inappropriate fishing gear, and environmental
problems such as drought, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
The Malawian government, said Mkandawire, had put in place a
number of measures to prevent the situation from getting out of
control.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry would encourage community-based fisheries
management schemes, apart from banning certain fishing gear, and
designating some times of the year as off-season for fishermen.
</P>
<P>
He added that some catchment areas of major rivers, which are
polluted, would be rehabilitated to act as breeding grounds for
fish, which would in turn migrate into the lake.
</P>
<P>
Lake Malawi with an area of 22,490 square kilometers is the
country's chief tourist attraction and home to more than 500
species of fish. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recovery of Chemical Fertilizer Industry Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- China's chemical fertilizer
industry recorded losses of 1.15 billion yuan (138.6 million US
dollars) during the January-September period due in part to
widespread heavy summer flooding, according to today's Market
Daily.
</P>
<P>
Some 57.1 percent of the nation's fertilizer companies operated
in the red during the period because of low demand and high import
volume, according to the article.
</P>
<P>
The reliance on imports in recent years has resulted for the
structural imbalance in fertilizer production. For example, the
nation produces ample nitrogenous fertilizers, but falls far short
in the production of phosphate and potash products.
</P>
<P>
Experts underlined that China should impose stringent controls
on the domestic fertilizer industry to prevent unapproved
companies from flooding the market with cheap inferior products.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they have called on the government departments to
ensure supplies of raw materials and waive taxes in order to
promote the recovery of the industry, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
