<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clashes Erupt Anew In East Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 3 (Xinhua)-- Clashes between Palestinians
and Israeli police erupted again on Thursday morning in East
Jerusalem after a Palestinian man was stabbed to death by an
Israel Jew in the previous day.
</P>
<P>
No casualties or injuries were reported so far.
</P>
<P>
Local Palestinian residents in the city, still angry about the
death of the young man, threw stones and rocks at Israeli police
near a post office on Salah Eddin Street of the Old City and
Israeli police tried to disperse them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local Palestinian residents in the city closed their
shops and halted all business Thursday to show their indignation
over the incident.
</P>
<P>
The 41-year old Usamah Mousa Al-Natsheh, father of six, was
stabbed to death early Wednesday by an Israeli Jew in the Old City
of Jerusalem. The police said the attacker wanted to cause
political problem in the city.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Palestinians clashed with Israeli police during
Natsheh's funeral Wednesday. Police responded by firing tear gas
and rubber-coated bullets. Several people were injured in the
clash. Angry Palestinians also set a vehicle on fire and
torched several other cars.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Jerusalem Mayor
Ehud Olmert strongly condemned the attack, saying such killings
can not be tolerated no matter the victim was a Jew or a
Palestinian.
</P>
<P>
Israel strengthened its security measures in East Jerusalem
following the implementation of the Wye peace accord signed in
October in Washington. However, incidents such as bombings and
killings have been occurring frequently in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
