<HEADLINE> Congolese (K) Rebel Leader to Consult Ugandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Rebel leaders in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) flew to Uganda Wednesday to
discuss the peace deal reached at the Franco-African summit in
Paris over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Rebel military leader Jean-Pierre Ondekane took off from the
eastern city of Kisangani Wednesday afternoon for two-day talks
with President Yoweri Museveni, the Monitor paper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But Presidential Press Secretary Hope Kivengere told Xinhua in
a telephone interview Thursday morning that she does not know the
meeting because the president is now touring the up-country and
will not return to Kampala until the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan State Minister of Defense Steven Kavuma refused to
make any comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Reuter's report as saying that the rebels'
political leader Ernest Wamba dia Wamba denied any big change
despite the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The fighting continued and the rebels would stand firm despite
mounting pressure from the offensive by the allied forces, Wamba
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been accused of backing the rebels who rose up to
out DRC President Laurent Kabila on August 2 while Kampala has
brushed aside the charge as baseless.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire reached in the Paris summit brings a new ray of
hope for the war-torn country. However, observers noted that it
may not be as binding to the rebels as expected because rebels
were not represented at the summit.  
</P>
