<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Nuclear Race Increases Tension in S. Asia (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The nuclear tests by India
and Pakistan in May this year have not only worsened the already
soured relations of the two neighboring countries, but also made
the situation in the South Asian region more tense.
</P>
<P>
India conducted five successive underground nuclear tests on
May 11 and 13, and Pakistan, in a tit-for-tat revenge, carried out
six nuclear tests on May 28 and 30. These tests have pushed the
two hostile countries as well as the whole region into a nuclear
armed race.
</P>
<P>
Indian Home Minister L. K. Advani said on May 18 that
"Islamabad should realize the change in the geo-strategic
situation in the region" following India's nuclear tests. Indian
Union Minister of Parliamentary Affairs and Tourism M. l. Khurana
said on May 21 that "India is ready to fight a fourth war with
Pakistan in case Pakistan wishes it so."
</P>
<P>
"If Pakistan wants to fight another war with us, they should
tell us the place and time, as we are ready for that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said in his first press
conference on May 23 after India's nuclear tests that "India has
resorted to nuclear blackmail to impose a military solution in
Kashmir... but any misadventure will be met with a resolute
response."
</P>
<P>
Following India's threat, Pakistan has put its army on maximum
alert along its border since May 20 and round-the-clock monitoring
systems have also been activated in the country.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Pakistan urged the world community to "take a
serious note of the irresponsible Indian threats."
</P>
<P>
Under their new threat perception and to face new challenges,
both India and Pakistan have quickened their efforts to develop
and manufacture more sophisticated weapons including nuclear
weapons and missiles.
</P>
<P>
Indian Admiral Vishnu Bhagwat said on November 30 that India's
naval version of the formidable missile Prithvi would be deployed
on-board certain surface ships by January 26 next year and its
newer submarines would be upgraded to have missile-launching
capability.
</P>
<P>
India has already begun manufacturing the 150-kilometer range
Prithvi missile for the Army and is in the process of developing
the 250-kilometer range version of the missile for the Air Force
for which test flights have already started. The sophisticated Sea
Harrier jump jets would undergo a "mid-life upgradation" within a
time frame and be fitted with "top-of-the-line avionics and
radar", he said.
</P>
<P>
Indian Defense Minister Geroge Fernandes said Wednesday that
the government has already approved the development of the longer
range (about 2,500 kilometers) missile Agni using state-of-the-art
technology.
</P>
<P>
Samar Mubarakmand, head of a Pakistan missile project, said
Wednesday that Pakistani scientists have built the most modern
surface-to-surface missile in the South Asian region and were
awaiting a government signal to launch it. The 759-kilometer range
new missile Shaheen is three times more powerful than India's
Prithvi missile.
</P>
<P>
Public opinions in the two countries hold that both India and
Pakistan have engaged themselves in an unnecessary war of nerves
which will hamper the social, cultural and economic ties between
them. They are of the view that the nuclear tests by the two
countries would lead to an arms race and proliferation of nuclear
weapons in the region, worsening the relations of the two
neighbors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Nuclear Race Increases Tension in S. Asia (2) ...two neighbors. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since May, armed clashes between India and Pakistan along the
Line of Control in the disputed Kashmir area have increased. In
their exchanges of fire, both sides used heavy weapons inflicting
heavy casualties.
</P>
<P>
Nawaz Sharif said in an interview with the India Today magazine
on June 6, "Kashmir is a flashpoint. It is the core issue. Only a
solution to that can lead to permanent peace in South Asia."
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan have fought three wars since 1947 and two of
them were due to the Kashmir dispute. India claims that Kashmir is
a part of its territory while Pakistan maintains that it is a
disputed area. They have talked over the issue on many occasions,
but without any result.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure of the world community, India and Pakistan
resumed their talks stalled after September last year in October
this year, and have since then held several rounds of talks at
various levels on issues including peace and security, Jammu and
Kashmir, trade and economy, but little has been achieved due to
deep mistrust between them.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Command and Staff College in Quetta on November
19, Sharif said that the recent bilateral talks between Pakistan
and India proved that "the Indians are not ready for meaningful
dialogue... Their primary objective is to deflect international
pressure and prevent the involvement of third parties in the
process."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has also described as complete failure the
Indo-Pakistan dialogue process.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said, "Our region will continue to be plagued with
tension, so long as the core issue of Jammu and Kashmir remains
unresolved." The world was shaken out of its indifference to the
cause of tension in South Asia, as the United Nations Security
Council and its five permanent members as well as the G-8 (Group
of Eight) have acknowledged that the unresolved Kashmir dispute is
the root cause of tension in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed on November 18
accused India of having expansionist designs in the region and
called for U.S. intervention. Speaking to a group of American
editors in Islamabad, he said that New Delhi had neither shown any
indication for settling the Kashmir dispute nor had accepted
Islamabad's proposal for nuclear restraint and stabilization.
</P>
<P>
Any further nuclear testing or more unsettling deployment by
either side will only heighten tensions in a region dangerously
close to open hostility. South Asia cannot afford a costly arms
race, the result of which can be only further impoverishment of
the people, diplomats here said.
</P>
<P>
Prices have gone up sharply with the smoke of nuclear tests in
India and Pakistan and the fiscal deficits of the two countries
are expected to increase by a big margin. In the wake of the
devaluation of their currencies, inflation rates have soared. The
big hike of price of daily necessities in India in recent months
have drawn severe criticism and resentment among people, who voted
out the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party' state governments in the
just-concluded assembly elections in Delhi and Rajasthan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
