<HEADLINE> Crime Seen as Philippines' 3rd Headache </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Next to inflation and
unemployment, crime is considered as the third most serious
problem in the Philippines, the Philippines News Agency said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted the latest survey of the Social Weather
Station covering the third quarter as saying that 9.4 percent of
the 2,400 respondents considered crime their most pressing
concern.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey showed that people in the country are
getting more confident of police responsiveness to crimes.
</P>
<P>
About 53 percent of the respondents said the police were fast
while 41 percent said they were slow. Only 6 percent said the
police did not respond at all.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, government officials announced the deployment of
more policemen in shopping malls and other areas expected to be
crowded during this coming holiday season.
</P>
<P>
Among the respondents, 27.2 percent of them considered
inflation and high prices as the most important problem while 23.7
percent of them put unemployment on top of the list of their
concerns.  
</P>
