<HEADLINE> SOCOG Saves Millions Dollars from Government's Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- An Australian government's
proposal would make Sydney Olympics organizing committee (SOCOG)
save 123 million U.S. dollars, Australia Olympics Minister
Michael Knight said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plan to minimize the effect of a goods-and-services tax on
the Sydney Olympics was put forward by Prime Minister John Howard
in a letter to New South Wales state Premier Bob Carr.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed legislation, most of SOCOG's contracts
involving ticket sales, sponsorships and television rights would
be free from the tax as exports.
</P>
<P>
The legislation would also apply to the Sydney Paralympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
Knight welcomed the plan although he said SOCOG would have
preferred a total exemption from the tax.
</P>
<P>
The ticket sales would reach a games record 372 million U.S.
dollars, according to SOCOG's budget.
</P>
<P>
The deal would depend on a Memorandum of Understanding between
the government and SOCOG being settled soon, Howard said. 
</P>
