<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance Industry Experiences Rapid Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's insurance sector has also accelerated efforts to open
wider to the outside world. American International Assurance
Co. Ltd. and Tokyo Marine and Fire Insurance Co. Ltd. emerged as
the first foreign insurance companies to establish operations in
China in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Eleven foreign insurance companies have since been granted
approval to do business in China and some 189 foreign companies
have opened representative offices.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 Foreign insurance companies recorded total premiums of
639 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The advanced management concepts and expertise foreign
insurance companies have introduced to China have helped to
develop and improve the nation's insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
For example, individual marketing means for life insurance
introduced from American International Assurance Company sparked
the rapid market development over a few years.
</P>
<P>
China's 1997 life insurance premiums hit 60 billion yuan, up a
dramatic 85 percent on the previous year. The volume showed that
for the first time in history life insurance premium exceeded
the volume for property insurance.
</P>
<P>
China has also developed its insurance business abroad over the
past few years with the establishment of companies such as the
China Reinsurance Company, People's Insurance Company of China
(H.K) and the European-China Insurance Holding Company. Related
companies currently have annual insurance premiums of several
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Insurance experts point to various problems and hidden risks in
China's rapidly developing insurance industry. The founding of the
CIRC is expected to help develop and improve China's insurance
market, unify supervisory activities and establish a supervision
system suited to the development of the socialist market economy
in order to ensure the sustained and sound development of the
nation's insurance industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grain Marketing Reform Yields Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- China has achieved initial
results in reducing government losses for grain purchases by
launching nationwide reform of the grain marketing system.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics released by the China Agricultural
Development Bank (CADB) show no losses for purchases by state
grain companies since.
</P>
<P>
CABD loans for purchases of grain and edible oil have increased
on a monthly basis since June this year, according to an article
in today's "People's Daily".
</P>
<P>
In terms of the summer harvest, the CADB has provided
sufficient loans for grain and rapeseed purchases in line with the
principle of "granting loans according to the volume of grain
purchased and collecting principal and interest in line with
market sales."
</P>
<P>
Government loans granted for purchases of grain and edible oil
over the past six months have equalled the purchasing value of the
two products.
</P>
<P>
Restructuring the grain distribution system represents a major
aspect of the central government's reform agenda for this year,
and is a main task for national economic development. Premier Zhu
Rongji has repeatedly stressed the importance and urgency for
reform of the grain marketing system.
</P>
<P>
The main problems with the nation's grain marketing system
center on the fact that state grain companies play a dual role
involving both storage and marketing, with the failure of
managements mechanisms to operate in line with the laws governing
market operations resulting in heavy financial losses.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that state grain companies have lost
more than 100 billion yuan over the past seven years due to poor
performance and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
The central government has responded by adopting a series of
measures to reverse the trend. For example, state grain companies
with sole rights to purchase grain directly from farmers are now
required to purchase surplus grain at protected prices.
</P>
<P>
The CADB has also granted loans totalling 2.3 billion yuan
during the first 10 months of this year for constructing temporary
granaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
