<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Cotton Colorant Not Acceptable in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Export Board of Zambia
(EBZ) has cautioned local exporters against exporting azo dye, a
cotton colorant, to Europe because the product is no longer
acceptable on that market, The Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
EBZ public relations officer, Leonard Simwanda, said in Lusaka
Wednesday that the European Union (EU) was becoming increasingly
conscious of the repercussions culminating from the importation
of products that were environmentally hazardous.
</P>
<P>
Simwanda explained that azo dye had been discovered to be a
health hazard to both producers and consumers in the EU.
</P>
<P>
He said although there was a wide market, the dye had been
found to be "highly" infectious and this had prompted the EU to
ban any imports of the dye into its market.
</P>
<P>
It is suspected that the dye is linked to the manifestation of
bladder cancer among workers exposed to the colorant, according
to the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
