<HEADLINE> Estrada Still Trying to Push for PAL-Cathay Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Thursday seemed determined to get Hong Kong-based Cathay
Pacific Airways to buy into Philippine Airline (PAL) despite the
breakdown of talks between the two airlines.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada told a press conference here that he remains
optimistic that the negotiations between the two airlines can
still be reopened when PAL chairman Lucio Tan returns from a trip
to Guam.
</P>
<P>
Cathay regional manager Peter Foster announced Wednesday the
pull-out of his company from six weeks of negotiations with PAL,
saying: "Certain issues could not be resolved." But he refused to
elaborate on these issues.
</P>
<P>
"The Cathay management wrote me a letter that they are still
available for another negotiations. So let us not lose hope," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada said when Tan returns to the country, "maybe
there is still a chance for them (PAL and Cathay) to come to an
agreement."
</P>
<P>
"When we asked them (Cathay) for help during the (PAL) strike,
I asked for help from Cathay and they responded and helped solve
many problems of the business," he said.
</P>
<P>
PAL was temporarily closed in September, following the labor
union's refusal to accept an agreement offered by the management,
calling for a suspension on collective bargaining agreement for 10
years, in exchange for shares in the national flag carrier. The
airline resumed operation in early October. 
</P>
