<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gates Donates 100 Million Dollars to Immunize Poor Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft founder Bill
Gates said Wednesday that he will donate 100 million U.S. dollars
to help vaccinate children in developing countries, according to
reports from the company.
</P>
<P>
"New life-saving vaccines quickly become available to children
in the developed world, but recent history shows us that children
in the developing world have to wait up to 15 years for the same
vaccine," Gates said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed,"We have a social imperative to work together
to address this basic inequality."
</P>
<P>
This is the second donation in a week that Gates and his wife
Melinda made. On November 25, they donated 20 million dollars to
the Seattle Public Library.
</P>
<P>
Bill Gates, who holds a 22 percent stake in the
65-billion-dollar Microsoft, is considered the richest man in
America and possibly the world.
</P>
<P>
Gates was once criticized for his lack of charity. But in
recent years, he has begun to make his mark as a philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, he established a two-billion-dollar William
H. Gates Foundation, which focuses on world health, population and
educational issues.
</P>
<P>
The Gates also established a 250-million-dollar Gates Library
Foundation to help libraries in poor communities gain access to
computer equipment and the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening Invigorating China: People's Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- People's Daily, China's leading
national newspaper, frontpaged an article hailing the
nation's opening policy as a highly successful approach to
invigorating the nation.
</P>
<P>
The article pointed out that China must make full use of
international and domestic markets and resources to supplement and
join the mainstream of the international economy.
</P>
<P>
The depth and breadth of the ongoing Asian financial crisis has
far exceeded people's predictions. The crisis has affected
China to some extent.
</P>
<P>
The article pointed out that China should persist in opening up
while continuing to strengthen the nation's ability to ward off
and prevent risks.
</P>
<P>
New problems and contradictions that have cropped up over the
past 20 years failed to restrict the further growth of China's
opening effort. The shift from a planned to a market economy, and
the shift in enterprise operational mechanism have not only
lagged behind demands for the opening drive, but have also
increased costs for opening.
</P>
<P>
A complete framework for micromanagement policies has not as
yet been formed, and direct administrative interference continues
to be so widespread as to reduce the effectiveness for resource
distribution.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the advantage of low cost labor in coastal areas
continues to weaken; an extensive foreign trade growth mode
cannot continue; and the structure of foreign-financed industries
is not rational.
</P>
<P>
The article noted: "The solutions to these problems lie in our
efforts to open wider to the outside world and to improve our
efficiency in opening up."
</P>
<P>
It called for a correct understanding of the relationship
between reform and opening, with the latter representing a
driving force behind the form. On the other hand, reform is the
precondition for opening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Dominant Taliban Fail to Bring Peace to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the international arena, the Pashtoon-dominated Taliban are
faced with even greater challenges.
</P>
<P>
The growing hostility between Iran and the Taliban was further
heightened in August, after nine Iranian diplomats and a
journalist were killed by the Taliban during their capture of the
key northern city of Mazar-e-Sharif, headquarters of the pro-Iran
northern alliance.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of accusations fueled the tension between the two
sides and raised the likelihood of war. In a show of strength,
Iran amassed approximately 200,000 soldiers along the border with
an implied threat to avenge the killing of its diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Central Asian states and Russia have also made a high-profile
reaction to the Taliban's continuing onslaught against the
opposition forces in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Russia, Tajikistan and Uzbekistan in October
signed another security pact providing for coordinated efforts to
halt the spread of "aggressive extremism." The three countries,
along with Kyrgyzstan and Kazakhstan, already have
Taliban-inspired treaties of mutual defense.
</P>
<P>
Even the Taliban's few foreign friends appear to be abandoning
the pariah regime. Saudi Arabia, one of the only three countries
(the other two being Pakistan and the United Arab Emirates) that
recognized the Taliban, essentially broke diplomatic ties with the
Taliban by recalling its envoy in Kabul and expelling the
militia's representative in Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
In Pakistan, considered to be the Taliban's closest friend
despite the government's repeated denial, there are consistent
strong voices urging the government to review its pro-Taliban
Afghan policy in order to straighten out its ties with other
regional countries.
</P>
<P>
Noticeably, the friendly relations between Pakistan and Iran
were strained over the Taliban's killing of Iranian diplomats.
Tehran, openly holding both Pakistan and the Taliban responsible
for the killing of Iranians, has already reduced its diplomatic
presence in Pakistan due to "security problems."
</P>
<P>
Against this backdrop, in doldrums are the international peace
efforts in Afghanistan spearheaded by the United Nations. On one
hand, the Afghan warring factions have apparently abandoned the
idea of peaceful negotiations and this leaves little room of
maneuver for the outside brokers.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the already fragile mutual trust between
Pakistan and Iran, which, among all external players, are
universally recognized as the two countries who can exert the
greatest influence on Afghanistan, was seriously undermined by the
recent developments in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. and the international community as a whole have not
given up on Afghanistan," said James Ngobi, acting head of the
U.N. Special Mission on Afghanistan, in a speech here at the
Institute of Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
"We in the U.N. have observed that peace will not come to
Afghanistan through conquest by military force," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban could be persuaded, if they hold onto their
conquests, to institute programs under which they would establish
a genuine multi-ethnic and representative system of administration
under the revered Afghan traditional Shuras (consultation group)
at all levels, Ngobi said.
</P>
<P>
"It is important therefore that Iran and Pakistan should resume
their bilateral discussions on the Afghan crisis. In particular,
they should revive their joint peace initiative, which was
instituted following the breakdown of the Ulema (Islamic scholars)
Commission process (in May)."
</P>
<P>
As for the so-called six-plus-two group of countries
(Afghanistan's six immediate neighbors plus Russia and the United
States), he said, "the present geo-military stature in Afghanistan
should impel them closer towards common ground, rather than
diverge them on the basis of individually conceived interests."
</P>
<P>
"Unless the above-mentioned proposals are seriously considered
and given a fair chance as basic minima, I believe that not only
will prospects for a peaceful settlement recede, but progress on
other attendant issues will also be slowed down," the U.N.
official concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Dominant Taliban Fail to Bring Peace to Afghanistan (1)  By Yang Shilong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 3 (Xinhua) -- With fighting, blood, death,
exodus, frustration and destruction, the year of 1998, just like
the past 20 years, meant anything but peace for tens of millions
of war-weary Afghans.
</P>
<P>
With the freezing winter approaching, fighting has escalated
over the recent weeks in northern Afghanistan between the dominant
Islamic Taliban and the opposition forces loyal to former Afghan
military chief Ahmad Masood as both sides attempted to secure
supply routes around the Hindu Kush mountain range.
</P>
<P>
Masood's spokesman Monday claimed that they have extended a
push across the far north after a popular revolt involving more
than 1,000 locals in Jouzjan province left 40 Taliban dead and
another 200 imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
The claim, if confirmed, would be the latest blow to the
Taliban, who now control more than 90 percent of Afghanistan
including the capital of Kabul following their sweeping victories
in the past few months in the north.
</P>
<P>
The hard-line militia have recently just admitted that Masood
had made extensive gains in the far northern Kunduz province
bordering Tajikistan. Both Kunduz and Jouzjan, which borders
neighboring Uzbekistan, encompass intricate supply routes linking
the north with Masood's stronghold in the Panjsher Valley.
</P>
<P>
The recent military advance by the Masood forces in northern
Afghanistan "is not only because of Masood's military acumen, but
is due to the Taliban's failure to introduce a political system
providing more space to the locals for accommodation," said
Zarghoon Shah Shinwari, an Afghan intellectual and journalist
working at a Pakistan-based Afghan research organization, in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
"With their rigid policies the Taliban are not in a position to
bring real peace to Afghanistan and successfully rule the
country," Shinwari said.
</P>
<P>
Shinwari is not alone in describing a less rosy future for the
formidable Taliban who suddenly rose to the Afghan political scene
in 1994 and vowed to impose their self-styled strict Islamic rule
in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Most observers here held that the Taliban militia might be able
to bring the remaining areas under their control. Yet given their
limited vision and experience of domestic governance and foreign
relations maneuvers, the Taliban's difficulties would increase,
not to say that the military balance in Afghanistan could be
changed any time as in the past.
</P>
<P>
One cannot deny that the puritanical Taliban did a good job in
improving law and order in areas under their writ but the present
situation has brought new demands to the forefront. Most Afghans
are least interested in the military conquests highly projected by
Taliban-controlled Radio Sharia. Instead, they want food for their
empty stomach, education for their children, rehabilitation of
their country, health and welfare facilities, and jobs and
business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban administration, seemingly more interested
in the strict implementation of the Islamic punishment, has not so
far presented any practical and feasible program to restore the
economy riddled by sky-rocketing prices of essential items, the
structureless banking system and the almost worthless Afghan
currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
