<BODY>
<HEADLINE> F16s Lease to Cost New Zealand 424M U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The 28 F16 fighter bombers
the New Zealand government plans to lease from the United States
for 10 years with an option to buy will cost 800 million NZ
dollars (424 million U.S. dollars) by the year 2011, according to
the Evening Post.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper Thursday quoted a spokesman for
New Zealand Defense Minister Max Bradford as saying the F16
fighter bombers, which will be acquired to replace the NZ Air
Force's 19 aging Skyhawk aircraft, were built for the Pakistan Air
Force but never delivered.
</P>
<P>
He told the Post the figure of 800 million NZ dollars
comprises:
</P>
<P>
-- A 10-year lease at 12.5 million NZ dollars a year, totaling
125 million NZ dollars;
</P>
<P>
-- Up to 204 million NZ dollars getting the planes operational,
which includes overhauling the engines, acquiring spares, support
and training of pilots and ground crew;
</P>
<P>
-- An option to buy at the end of 10 years at about 140 million
 U.S. dollars (264 million NZ dollars at the current exchange
rate); and
</P>
<P>
--About 200 million NZ dollars in operating costs.
</P>
<P>
The Post said the New Zealand Air Force intends to operate only
 22 of the aircraft. The other six will be kept as "attrition
aircraft" or broken down for spares.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Press Association (NZPA) reported Thursday that
the F16 fighters New Zealand will lease "are ready to fly without
 modifications".
</P>
<P>
They were built in two lots, in 1989 and 1992. Though they were
early models, they incorporated all the modifications and
upgrades included since the first F16s were built in 1974, the
NZPA said.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand will take delivery of the fighters in 2001 if the
deal is done, it added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
