<HEADLINE> Workload Bigger Worry Than Money: New Zealand Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Workloads, stress and lack
of time for research are of even more concern to university
academic staff than salaries in New Zealand, the Dominion reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper said that a survey conducted by
the New Zealand Council for Educational Research, finds that
academic staff work an average of 53 hours a week and expect this
to continue, to the detriment of research.
</P>
<P>
It also finds that the main concern of academics about salaries
is that they are no longer competitive with international
universities, or the private sector and professions.
</P>
<P>
The survey says 40 percent of university academic staff suffer
frequent job stress, with work-related illness or injury up from
30 percent in a 1994 survey to 40 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 90 percent of academic staff take work home and about a
third of general staff, who average 40 hours, work unpaid
overtime. More than half of academic and support staff such as
technicians think they are underpaid.
</P>
<P>
President-elect Jane Kelsey of the New Zealand Association of
University Staff was quoted as saying that the ability of New
Zealand universities to recruit overseas will be severely limited
if workloads and stress continue to increase.
</P>
<P>
Massive workloads are endangering staff health and
universities' future viability, she said.
</P>
<P>
The survey covered a random sample of 30 percent of academics
and technicians and half of support staff in all seven
universities. The response rate was 55 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
