<HEADLINE> New Zealand PM Outlines Agenda for Next APEC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley has outlined the agenda for the APEC Leaders'
Informal Meeting to be held in New Zealand next September.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a businessmen's gathering in Christchurch, the
biggest city in New Zealand's South Island, Shipley said Thursday
that as APEC Chair in 1999, New Zealand "can shape the APEC agenda
to restore confidence in our region".
</P>
<P>
In her speech, which was released here by the Prime Minister's
Office, Shipley said the agenda New Zealand has set covers four
important areas. In 1999 New Zealand wants to see:
</P>
<P>
-- further substantive progress towards reducing the barriers
to and costs of trade and investment;
</P>
<P>
-- a credible APEC response to the economic crisis;
</P>
<P>
-- strengthening of the institutions and human resources in
this region to deal with the economic challenges APEC members all
face; and
</P>
<P>
-- The building of broader support for APEC among the wider
communities.
</P>
<P>
"I am determined and confident that we should undertake our
chairing responsibilities with a sense of flair as well as
professionalism. As host economy in 1999 we will chair all of the
Ministerial meetings and the Leaders' summit," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We have a responsibility to carry forward the existing work of
the group and the outcomes from Kuala Lumpur provide a platform
for doing this," Shipley added.
</P>
<P>
Realistically, the New Zealand prime minister added, "we can
not expect APEC to make a great leap forward each year.
Incremental progress, while not as exciting or headline grabbing,
may prove more significant and sustainable in the long run."
</P>
</TEXT>
