<HEADLINE> Italian Premier Supports EU Initiative to Try Ocalan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema said on Wednesday that he backed the European Union (EU)
initiative to try Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan before an
international tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Opening a Lower House debate over the Ocalan case, D'Alema said
the EU initiative would contribute to a peaceful solution to the
dispute with Turkey which wants him extradited on terrorism
charges.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema, who discussed the initiative with other EU nations,
said the proposal would be "of great value" because the crisis was
not related to Italy or Turkey alone, but to all European nations.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Prime Minister told deputies that Italy was ready
to support the Kurdish people, but "this does not mean to support
of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was detained in Rome on November 12 under international
arrest warrants issued by Germany and Turkey, but Germany later
said it would not seek Ocalan's extradition.
</P>
<P>
Italian law forbids extradition to a country that practices
the death penalty, which is in force in Turkey. 
</P>
