<HEADLINE> ADB to Provide Loan for Bangladesh Mangrove Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has approved a 37 million U.S. dollar loan for a project of the
Bangladesh's Sundarbans Reserve Forest, part of the world's
largest remaining mangrove area, an ADB official said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With this loan, Bangladesh will develop a sustainable
management and biodiversity conservation system of the Sundarbans,
situated in the southwestern part of the country, the ADB official
told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bangladesh will use the loan to introduce modern
management systems involving all stakeholders in 17 sub-districts
around the forest.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is also providing a technical assistance grant of
570,000 dollars to determine a future option for the Sundarbans'
development.
</P>
<P>
The participatory systems will conserve and manage the forest
and its biodiversity as a multi-dimensional resource.
</P>
<P>
The 6,000 square kilometer mangrove area provides a subsistence
living for 3.5 million people, offers protection from cyclones in
Southwest Bangladesh and is rich in biodiversity and natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
As a globally significant ecosystem, the Sundarbans Reserve
Forest contains habitats for fish, shrimps, birds and other
wildlife, including the largest remaining population of the highly
endangered Bengal tiger.
</P>
<P>
The resources of the forest are being depleted through
increasing use by commercial wood processors, rural communities
bordering the forest and subsistence fisher-folk from the Bay of
Bengal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
