<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Contribute to IMF Rescue Plan for Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Australia is to lend up to
half a billion Australian dollars (300 million U.S. dollars) to an
International Monetary Fund (IMF) rescue package for Brazil,
Australian Treasurer Peter Costello announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Costello said the loan is an interim measure under the IMF New
Arrangements to Borrow (NAB), which he chairs, and the funds
should be repaid early in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"They are being provided at an above-market interest rate,"
Costello said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The NAB came into effect just two weeks ago following
ratification by the United States and Germany, bringing together
25 developed nations into a more streamlined operation for
assisting with IMF financial rescue packages.
</P>
<P>
The Brazil package is the first time the NAB had been
activated, as members have agreed to provide up to 19.9 billion
Australian dollars (12 billion U.S. dollars), the treasurer said
in a separate statement.
</P>
<P>
"The total funding being provided by the IMF to Brazil in
support of its reform program is 17.89 billion U.S. dollars. The
World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank and a group of
bilateral supporters will also provide assistance to Brazil in
conjunction with the IMF, " the treasurer said.
</P>
<P>
"The total support from all official sources is around 41.6
billion U.S. dollars."
</P>
<P>
The treasurer defended Australia's assistance for a country far
removed from its local region. "Our membership of the NAB
represents a global obligation and the Brazilian program is
crucial for efforts to control the current international financial
crisis, which began in Asia but has since spread more widely."
</P>
<P>
"Stability in Brazil is important for stability elsewhere in
Latin America and for stability in the international financial
system," he added.
</P>
<P>
Although Australia has contributed billions of dollars to IMF
rescue packages for Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea during the
past year, this is the first time it is to lend money to help a
country outside Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
