<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Rescue Package for Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) decided Wednesday to help revive Brazil's economy with
a fresh cash injection of 18.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
An IMF statement said the credit line is part of a 41.5 billion
dollars international rescue package agreed upon on November 13 by
officials of the IMF and the largest Latin American economy.
</P>
<P>
Of the newly earmarked money, 5.3 billion dollars would be
available immediately and an additional 4.5 billion dollars at the
end of February, after government reform programs are reviewed.
</P>
<P>
Additional payments by the IMF are scheduled later in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, however, can have access to the second installment
before February if the government decides it cannot wait for the
funds and receives the IMF governing board's approval.
</P>
<P>
The three-year IMF rescue package committed Brazil to avert a
devaluation of its currency by reducing its 65 million dollars
budget deficit through spending cuts, tax hikes and other measures.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB)
would contribute 4.5 billion dollars each to the package, with a
further 14.5 billion dollars to come from other donor nations.
</P>
<P>
The United States is the largest contributor among these
countries with a commitment of five billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
