<HEADLINE> Thailand Encourages Counter-Trade Deals With EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government encourages
state firms to pursue counter-trade deals with the European Union
for Thai agricultural products that will face higher tariffs
staring from January 1, 1999, a government official said.
</P>
<P>
Counter-trade would also help state enterprises save money, The
Bangkok Post Thursday quoted Apinant Pavanarit, director-general
of the European Affairs Department at the Foreign Ministry, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, meanwhile, is looking for new markets in Eastern
Europe and Latin America for Thai agricultural products to offset
possible declines in the EU once tariffs increase, Apinant said.
</P>
<P>
The EU is removing three major Thai export sectors -- fishery
products, fresh fruit and vegetables, and cut flowers -- from its
Generalized System of Preferences (GSP). Under the GSP designed to
help the beneficiaries build markets abroad, developing countries
can export certain products to the EU at lower tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Apinant met on Wednesday with representatives of 14 state
enterprises to promote the counter-trade idea. The 14 enterprises
include the Communications Authority of Thailand, Thai Airways
International, Metropolitan Rapid Transit Authority, Electricity
Generating Authority, State Railway of Thailand and the Port
Authority of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Apinant reaffirmed that the ministry would continue to lobby
the EU to postpone the GSP removal until 2001. But Deputy Prime
Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said last week that the effort
would be futile.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said the government should concentrate instead on
lobbying the EU to make comprehensive changes in its tariff
structure. He argued that EU tariffs on many imported goods are
much higher than in markets such as North America and Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
