<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serb Republic Condemns Arrest of General by SFOR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Petar Djokic, president of the
Bosnian Serb parliament, on Wednesday condemned NATO's
Stabilization Force (SFOR) for arresting the Republika Srpska's
most senior military figure.
</P>
<P>
General Radislav Krstic, commander of the 5th Corps of the
Bosnian Serb Army, was arrested on his way to a general staff
meeting near Bijeljina, in the north of the Bosnian Serb republic
controlled by U.S. troops serving in SFOR, around midday Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He was indicted by the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal for
genocide, complicity to commit genocide, extermination, murder,
and persecution for his alleged personal involvement in atrocities
and his command of troops carrying out massacres.
</P>
<P>
According to Tanjug news agency, Djokic said, "General Radislav
Krstic's name was never placed on any list of war criminals by the
international criminal tribunal in The Hague."
</P>
<P>
He noted that this behavior of international forces "brings
uncertainty to people, a feeling that every citizen of the
(Bosnian) Serb republic can be regarded as a potential war
criminal in the eyes of the tribunal, and that SFOR is authorized
to arrest anybody, anytime, anywhere."
</P>
<P>
Tanjug reported that Louise Arbour, chief prosecutor of the
International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia (ICTY),
verified Wednesday in The Hague that Krstic was arrested on a
secret indictment issued by her on October 30 and confirmed by a
judge three days later. But the document was kept sealed until
Wednesday in order to facilitate his arrest, she revealed.
</P>
<P>
"Persons indicted for war crimes who are still at large should
realize they, too, will be brought to justice", NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana said Wednesday after the arrest,
adding that Krstic would be sent to The Hague tribunal for trial.
</P>
<P>
Krstic is the ninth war crimes suspect to be arrested in the
former Yugoslavia by peace-keeping forces. He was named head of
the Drina Corps of the Bosnian Serb Army in 1995 after the fall of
Srebrenica. 
</P>
</TEXT>
