<HEADLINE> Bolivians Celebrate UNESCO's Naming of World Heritage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAMAIPATA, Bolivia, December 2 (Xinhua) -- About 5,000 people
gathered here on Wednesday for a party after the United Nations
Education, Science and Culture Organization (UNESCO) declared an
ancient fort in Bolivia a world heritage site.
</P>
<P>
The Samaipata fort, 120 kilometers southeast of the city of
Santa Cruz, was built under several pre-Incan cultures although
the Incas lived on the site when the Spanish first landed in
America in 1542.
</P>
<P>
The fort was built on a militarily strategic site, based on a
hill 1,900 meters above sea level overlooking all routes leading
from the valleys to the tropical jungle.
</P>
<P>
A 200-meter long and 90-meter wide building inside the fort is
adorned with zoomorphic figures representing felines and snakes.
</P>
<P>
Samaipata received its new status at the 22nd UNESCO meeting
held on Wednesday in the Japanese city of Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
The fort is made up of two sites, the hill which with its
ancient engravings could have been a ceremonial site of the
ancient city in the 14th and 15th centuries, and a zone south of
the hill which was possibly its administrative and residential
district.
</P>
<P>
Samaipata mayor Alfonso Banegas said the fort was used as a
ceremonial site by various cultures for moon and water worship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
