<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Port No Longer Suffering From Traffic Jams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- One of the greatest changes at
the port of Shanghai in the past two decades, according to Wan
Jiazhong, a ship captain for COSCO Shanghai, is the lack of
traffic jams on the sea lanes.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Wan explains, in the past they often had to wait
offshore for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
From the late '70s to the early '80s, Shanghai had some of the
worst traffic jams in its harbor with the rapidly-growing number
of vessels coming in owing to the boom in foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 vessels could be often seen moored offshore in
the Yangtze River mouth, recalls Li Jisan, and this did not help
the port's name and caused considerable losses.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the bottle-neck problem, the government spent 8.46
billion yuan (1.02 billion US dollars) expanding the port's docks
and berths, which can now handle 930,000 tons of goods.
</P>
<P>
Since 1984, the port has handled more than 100 million tons of
goods annually and has become the world's 11th largest container
port. It is expected to handle 3 million TEUs this year.
</P>
<P>
It has forged business ties with more than 400 ports and 600
shipping companies in over 160 foreign countries and regions and
with the new information network, the amount of time required to
handle vessels has been cut drastically.
</P>
<P>
Vessels had to stay in the port an average of 9.5 days, some 20
years ago, but that time has now been shortened to 1.9 days.
</P>
<P>
Captain Wan Jiazhong says that his container ship normally
stays in the port about 12 hours, and sometimes, needs only 5 or 6
hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
