<HEADLINE> UNDP Report Accuses Tamil Rebels of Intransigence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Development Program
(UNDP) Wednesday accused the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE) of delaying a solution to the ethnic conflict in Sri Lanka
by constantly refusing to negotiate a political solution.
</P>
<P>
"As long as the LTTE remains implacable in its refusal to
accept any political solution short of a separate state and
engages in armed violence to support its position, it is difficult
to end the conflict situation," the UNDP said in the National
Human Development Report on Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The 88-page report, compiled by a group of independent experts,
said the LTTE deliberately attacked institutions in areas outside
the northern and eastern provinces.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a 15-year war for a separate Tamil
state in the north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
The report urged expatriate Tamils, foreign governments and
diplomatic circles to exert pressure on the LTTE to cease
violence, tolerate democratic Tamil political parties and
negotiate a political settlement rather than insist on a separate
state.
</P>
<P>
It stressed the need for a broad consensus on a political
solution to the conflict among the people including the government
and other political parties.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's relatively high level of social development was
praised by the report.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP said the contents of the report remain the
responsibility of the independent analysts who compiled it after
extensive investigations and research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
