<HEADLINE> Macedonia Approves Deployment of NATO Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Macedonia's new government
Wednesday approved NATO's request to deploy in Macedonia rapid
reation troops for possible intervention in Kosovo, according to
news reports from the Macedonian capital of Skopje.
</P>
<P>
"This is a big decision made by the new government at the very
beginning of its mandate but it will contribute to Macedonia's
speedier integration with NATO," said Prime Minister Ljubco
Georgievski, when announcing the decision following a cabinet
discussion on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new government was formed after a recent election and won a
confidence vote in parliament on Monday.
</P>
<P>
As called for by a NATO decision on November 13, a 1,700-
member rapid reaction force will be deployed in Macedonia, which
neighbors Kosovo, to protect the 2,000 monitors of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
assigned to the Yugoslav province in case they are at risk there.
</P>
<P>
After NATO Secretary-general Javier Solana struck a deal with
Macedonia President Kiro Gligorov and Prime Minister Georgievski,
a 30-member advance team arrived in Skopje on November 28 to
prepare for the arrival of the rapid reaction troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
