<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Help Finance Second Bridge Over Danube </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria is prepared to help pay
for a second bridge crossing over the Danube linking up with
Romania, Bulgarian Deputy Prime Minister Evgenii Bakurdjiev said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Following a two-day conference with Romanian and Greek
ministers charged with environment and communications, Bakurdjiev
said the construction could be completed within three years and
the cost was estimated at 120 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said 60 million dollars would come from the European
Investment Bank, another 30 million dollars from European Union
bodies, and the rest, accounting for no more than 30 million
dollars, would be committed by Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria and Romania, sharing 400 kilometers of the Danube as
their border, had proposed to jointly build a second bridge to
ease the burden on the old bridge, but the proposal was deadlocked
over disagreement on the choice of bridge site.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Minister of Water, Forests and Environment Romulus
Tomescu, who attended the three-nation meeting, has expressed his
discontent with the site Bulgaria selected, hoping that the two
nations could continue to work out a better choice.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the trilateral meeting also adopted a joint
declaration to establish three working groups made up of
Bulgarian, Romanian and Greek experts to speed up implementation
of joint infrastructure, transport and environmental projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
