<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Democrat Says Memos Not Relevant to Clinton Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The ranking Democrat on the
U.S. House Judiciary Committee said on Wednesday that a review of
secret campaign finance memos had found they were not "in any way
relevant" to the inquiry into President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Representative John Conyers said the review by Democratic
counsel Kevin Simpson had not found anything in the documents to
merit consideration by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
"We trust that this closes a short and unproductive chapter in
the history of this very strange proceeding," Conyers said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Simpson and Republican chief investigative
counsel David Schippers read the memos on potential White House
fund-raising irregularities during Clinton's 1996 re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Republican committee members had no immediate reaction
Wednesday after Schippers viewed the memos.
</P>
<P>
Chief U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson ruled earlier
Wednesday that one Republican and one Democratic staff member
could see the memos, but could not make copies or take notes and
had to report the contents only to Chairman Henry Hyde and ranking
Democrat John Conyers.
</P>
<P>
The memos, written by FBI Director Louis Freeh and former
campaign finance task force head Charles LaBella, recommended the
appointment of an independent counsel to investigate the White
House fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
Republicans subpoenaed the documents after receiving a tip that
the memos, which include confidential information from grand
juries under Johnson's jurisdiction, might contain evidence of
criminal wrongdoing by Clinton. They have also subpoenaed Freeh
and LaBella to give closed-door depositions.
</P>
<P>
"The majority's sudden lurch into the subject of campaign
finance is ill-advised and simply a last-ditch attempt to
resuscitate a dying investigation," Conyers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
