<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Accurate Predictions Help Keep Earthquake Casualties Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMIN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Timely pre-warning of recent
earthquakes in Yunnan Province in southwest China has helped keep
the number of casualties down, a senior seismologist said here
today.
</P>
<P>
He Xihu, vice-director of the Yunnan Seismology Bureau, said
that seismologists in the predicted that earthquakes measuring 5.9
would hit Ninglang County before November 20 and warned local
people.
</P>
<P>
On November 19, two tremors measuring 5.0 and 6.2 hit 13
townships in the area, killing three and injuring 1,381. This was
the smallest number of deaths for all earthquakes of the same
magnitude that have hit the province, He said.
</P>
<P>
The local government got the warning a week ahead of time and
was able to act to get people out of old houses and a
round-the-clock watch was started. The two earthquakes damaged
17,500 houses, 395 school buildings, some water conservation
projects, bridges, and highways, causing economic losses of 590
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The low mortality rate can also be attributed to the time, he
said. The first quake hit at 19:31 on November 19, and many people
ran out to open fields before the second, stronger quake hit seven
minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Quick rescue work also helped. In less than five hours, rescue
workers got to the scene and rushed people with serious injuries
to local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan lies in an earthquake belt, along with Gansu, Shaanxi
and Sichuan provinces, and this is an active period for
earthquakes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
