<HEADLINE> Copper Prices Dip to 11-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Building up of inventories
worldwide has downed copper prices to the 11-year low of average
69.4 cents a pound, the Chilean Copper Commission said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As accumulated inventories of copper in New York and London had
reached over 150,000 metric tons this year, the commission said,
prices were hovering around 70 cents per pound in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Although far below the expected price of 92 cents a pound, the
recent dip was within expectations, it said. The average so far
this year is 75.66 cents, within the predicted 75-80 cents range.
</P>
<P>
Chile, a leading copper producer in the world, receives 40
percent of the government revenues from copper.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean Copper Commission said it expects copper prices to
go up in December and to average over 75 cents per pound for the
year, and further up to 70-75 cents next year and through year
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
