<HEADLINE> Thai FM Urges ASEAN to Accept Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan has urged Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
members to be ready to make political and economic changes, The
Bangkok Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN "has to be ready to make adjustments" or it risks being
compelled to do so by force beyond its control, Surin was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot sit still and take comfort behind the status quo or
continue to do business as usual. We all must be prepared to
adjust ourselves and accommodate the pressures and demands of the
changing times," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Being willing to adjust yourself is better than being dictated
to adjust," he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN members, he said, must be prepared to heed calls "for
reform, for greater democracy and for wider participation of our
peoples in the political and economic processes."
</P>
<P>
Surin was speaking at a two-day conference of Asian
intellectuals convened to discuss the Asian economic crisis by the
Japan Center for International Exchange and the Singapore-based
Institute of Southeast Asian Studies.
</P>
<P>
Delving into the history of ASEAN, Surin said, "in the
beginning, 30 or 31 years ago, diversity of ASEAN was our strength
-- the fact that we were different. Lately, particularly,
political diversity has become our problem."
</P>
<P>
But he said adapting and adjusting to globalization does not
mean that traditions and values that reflect the best of ASEAN
societies need no longer be protected and conserved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
