<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors in U.S. Real Estate More Cautious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners planning
investment in U.S. real estate in 1999 are somewhat more cautious
than they were last year, according to a survey released Wednesday
by the Association of Foreign Investors in Real Estate (AFIRE).
</P>
<P>
This is against the background of a new wave of opportunities
for foreign investors in U.S. real estate created by their
domestic turmoil in both real estate investment trusts (REITs) and
real estate capital markets.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question that the optimism of foreign investors
has been tempered by continuing concerns about a global
recession," said AFIRE.
</P>
<P>
Of the 145 AFIRE members representing 17 countries, only 42
percent of respondents to the survey said they would increase
their investment in 1999, as compared with 67 percent in 1997 who
said they would increase their investment in the forthcoming year.
</P>
<P>
With over 22 billion U.S. dollars invested in the country's
real estate, AFIRER's member investments represent nearly two
thirds of all direct foreign investment in U.S. real estate.
</P>
<P>
Last year at this time, AFIRE said, foreign investors faced
fewer opportunities due to very strong competition from REITs that
reduced inventory and sent prices sky-rocketing. But this year,
the product is more accessible.
</P>
<P>
Office buildings were ranked as the number one investment
opportunity in the U.S. today, and 37 percent of respondents said
they would add office buildings to their portfolio in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But their interest in industrial and hotel properties is
declining, with only 3 percent have hotels on their list.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, survey respondents picked multi-family properties as
the second most attractive real estate product in the U.S. today.
Since 1995, it has been in the third, fourth or fifth position.
</P>
<P>
When asked to rank the top five U.S. cities for foreign
investment, respondents could agree overwhelmingly on only
four: Washington, New York, San Francisco and Boston. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
