<HEADLINE> Kidd Gets Permission to Talk with Blackburn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- English Premier League club
Manchester United have relented in the battle to hang on to
manager Alex Ferguson's assistant Brian Kidd.
</P>
<P>
Blackburn was given permission Wednesday to discuss the Ewood
Park managerial vacancy with Kidd, linked with the Rovers post
after the sacking of former chief Roy Hodgson.
</P>
<P>
The news was released following Blackburn's 1-0 defeat in the
Worthington Cup semi-final at Leicester on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Rovers club chairman Robert Coar said: "We have received
permission tonight from Manchester United to speak to Brian Kidd.
</P>
<P>
"During the next 24 hours, we will be meeting Brian Kidd. That
is all the club are saying on this matter at this time," he added.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United have been reluctant to part with Kidd, with
approaches having been made by Everton last summer and Manchester
City.
</P>
<P>
Kidd spent Wednesday night alongside Alex Ferguson, possibly
for the last time, as United also went out of the Worthington Cup
at Spurs.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson had been keen to hang onto his loyal lieutenant, and
had earlier said: "We do not want to lose Brian. He is very
important to United.
</P>
<P>
"We have built up an excellent staff and Brian has been a key
part, " he said.
</P>
<P>
United initially rejected Rovers' approach for Kidd, who has
been Ferguson's right-hand man for almost eight years.
</P>
<P>
Kidd has long been tipped, along with Middlesbrough boss Bryan
Robson, as a possible successor to Ferguson when the United
manager decides to retire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
