<HEADLINE> UNDP Issues Sri Lankan Human Development Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Development Program
(UNDP) Wednesday issued a Sri Lankan Human Development Report
prepared by a group of independent experts, the official Daily
News said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The group includes a six-member national team, an international
consultant from the U.N. Children's Fund, India and a special
consultative committee headed by former UNDP Resident
Representative Arve Ofstad.
</P>
<P>
Head of the six-member national team Harsha Aturupane said the
88-page report is an analysis of human development in terms of
achievements, poverty levels and gender empowerment, categorized
by regional, district and provincial dimensions.
</P>
<P>
UNDP Resident Representative Peter Witham in his comments on
the report observed that dimensions may have been omitted in this
maiden summary and are expected to be incorporated in its future
analytical reports.
</P>
<P>
Witham pointed out that the main aim of the report is to
basically depict the current social and economic situation of the
country and to stimulate strategies for development activities
based on the country's identified strengths and weakness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
