<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Displaying Its Best Tomb Frescoes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- China will put its most treasured
ancient frescoes on display in Xi'an, the capital of Shaanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
The Shaanxi History Museum is planning on turning an
underground hall into a 3,000-square meter exhibition center for
the original frescoes from tombs of the Tang Dynasty (618-907).
</P>
<P>
The 540 frescoes have been kept in a museum storehouse that
only a few scholars and distinguished overseas guests could see.
</P>
<P>
It has some of the most precious frescoes in the world,
according to Feng Gengwu, the deputy curator of the museum, which
has 18 state treasures among them and 82 that are designated as
class-one cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists have found beautiful frescoes inside tombs,
especially from the Tang, one of China's most prosperous
periods. In Shaanxi they have excavated 66 Tang tombs that have
frescoes, which provide a panorama of people's lives in the Tang
Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
One purpose of the exhibition is to put the frescoes in a
better place because the storehouse is not ideal for preservation
or display, Feng explains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tomb Frescoes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After the frescoes were moved from the plastered wall it was
difficult to preserve them, so museum authorities built the
1,500-sq.m. storehouse in 1992. Even moving the giant cabinets
that original held the frescoes can do some damage, Feng says.
</P>
<P>
Protecting frescoes is now a business with world-class
difficulties, according to Shen Qinyan, director of the museum's
fresco research center, and they are focusing on problems like
fading colors and a peeling coat.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese cultural relics research institute has cooperated
with the museum in finding ways of protecting them and has
provided equipment to analyze the colors, and some progress has
been made.
</P>
<P>
But, researchers still want visitors to be able to see the
treasures as a whole, so Shen says, they will recreate tomb
passages in the proposed exhibition hall and put the frescoes on
the wall.
</P>
<P>
The museum estimates the total cost at 25 million yuan (3
million U.S. dollars). Cultural organizations from Italy and
France have also shown an interest in the endeavor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban President Opens Latin American Economic System Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Cuban President Fidel Castro on
Wednesday opened a ministerial meeting of the Latin American
Economic System (SELA) with a call to revitalize economic thinking
in the face of international economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Castro said that despite its fund
shortage, the group was boosting the unity of Latin American and
Caribbean countries by dealing with world financial troubles and
damage caused by Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
Castro urged economists to analyze the future of the region
where there was a lack of new prospects and ideas.
</P>
<P>
Speeches were also made by SELA permanent secretary Carlos
Moneta and the executive secretary of the Latin American and
Caribbean Economic Commission, Jose Antonio Ocampo.
</P>
<P>
The two-day ministerial meeting, the 24th of its kind, was
preceded by two days of discussions between representatives of the
28 member countries on an annual report of the permanent
secretariat, its restructuring and proposals to help Central
American countries affected by Hurricane Mitch in their
reconstruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
