<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Company Developing Advanced Fighter Jet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian
aeronautics company Embraer is developing an advanced fighter and
training jet, according to newspaper reports on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new AMX-T jet, to be equipped with an on-board radar and
AR-AR missiles, will have a speed of up to 1,035 kilometers per
hour and a 3.5-ton load capacity.
</P>
<P>
The new jet is being developed from the old AMX fighter model,
which has been in use by the Brazilian Air Force since the late
1980s.
</P>
<P>
Embraer President Mauricio Novis Botelho said his company is
aiming at producing an unsophisticated plane that would be sold at
a low cost around the world. Intelligent electronic components
are being designed for the plane's navigation and combat systems.
</P>
<P>
The 40-million-U.S.-dollar project also includes construction
of 32 planes for the Air Force, which will test-fly in the year
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Party Hopes to Win 1999 General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's United Development
Party (PPP) wound up its fourth congress Wednesday night with a
strong commitment to bring the party toward a better future and
win next year's general election.
</P>
<P>
"We have two political agenda items to safeguard," said the
Muslim-backed party's newly-elected General Chairman Hamzah Haz at
the closing ceremony here.
</P>
<P>
He said the agenda items are the June 1999 general election and
the presidential and vice presidential nominations in the general
assembly of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) by the end of
1999.
</P>
<P>
Hamzah, now the state minister of investment, defeated his main
rival, Food and Horticulture Minister Ahmad Muflih Saefuddin, by a
majority of votes at Wednesday's election.
</P>
<P>
Hamzah expressed optimism that the party could increase the
votes in the upcoming polls if all members of the newly-formed PPP
Executive Board along with its loyal cadres and followers work
hard.
</P>
<P>
"We have the responsibility to enable this party to gain more
votes than it had achieved in the 1997 elections in which it
managed only to secure 22.5 percent," he was quoted by Antara News
Agency Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
One of the only three political parties allowed under former
President Soeharto's rule, PPP always ranked second to the ruling
Golkar (Functional Group) in general elections. The party got 89
seats in the 500-member House of Representatives in last year's
election.
</P>
<P>
PPP was formed from the fusion of four Islamic political
parties and organizations in 1973. They were Nahdlatul Ulama (NU),
Muslimin Indonesia (MI), Perti and Syarikat Islam.
</P>
<P>
Hamzah's victory marked the first time that a member of the NU
camp assumes the party's top post since the party's birth. In the
past, the party was never chaired by NU cadres despite the fact
the NU became the main source of PPP votes in every general
election and Hamzah supporters warned the congress if Hamzah was
not elected, there would be a significant decline in the PPP vote.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Hamzah's victory, a political analyst from the
Indonesian Institute of Science Indria Samego said any NU cadre
could have won the PPP chairmanship at every congress if there had
been no interference from the government.
</P>
<P>
Under former President Soeharto, no politician was able to lead
the party if the government did not like him, Samego was quoted by
the Indonesian Observer Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hamzah's election raised hopes that he would draw NU members
back to PPP, the Jakarta Post said, adding that NU members'
political affiliations have become increasingly scattered, with
some joining the ruling Golkar, others signing up with the new
crop of parties and some keeping neutral.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility that PPP would be allied with such Islamic
political parties as the NU-backed National Awakening Party and
the National Mandate Party led by Amien Rais, Hamzah said PPP
welcomed cooperation with any party.
</P>
<P>
"We are open for whoever. The most important thing is that we
must have good access to the elections. If we only get five or 10
percent of the votes, it would be meaningless because nobody would
then respect us," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
