<HEADLINE> World Bank Offers Loan to Brazil to Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will
provide Brazil with 165 million U.S. dollars in loan to help the
country fight against AIDS, the Jornal do Brasil daily reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Health Minister Jose Serra will sign the loan
agreement next week in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to fund the 1999-2002 AIDS program phase
II, which will focus on preventing contagion among people living
in extreme poverty, who make up most of the AIDS victims.
</P>
<P>
A total of 300 million dollars is needed for the program. The
Brazilian government will bear the rest of the fund.
</P>
<P>
With the program, health authorities will be able to increase
threefold the number of cities receiving medicine, condoms and
other devices.
</P>
<P>
Some 400,000 people have been registered as HIV-positive in
Brazil, of whom 135,000 have developed full-blown AIDS, the news
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
