<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Real Estate Markets to Remain Strong in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The real estate market in
the United States is expected to remain strong in 1999 because the
underlying fundamentals of property performance this year have
remained solid even in the face of sagging financial markets, a
leading real estate investment banking firm said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Examining trends that are expected to affect the sectors of
office, lodging and retail in 1999, Sonnenblick-Goldman Company
said in a report that the markets have learned from past mistakes
and are in a better position to manage the downside, while taking
advantage of opportunities.
</P>
<P>
While 1999 may not be a boom year, real estate, equity and debt
will remain solid investments, the company said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the markets are becoming increasingly global as
corporations have broken their national borders and have been
doing business worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Traditional lenders, including insurers, banks and pension
funds, will become bigger players in real estate as the more
aggressive investment banks, which have dominated the more highly
leveraged deals, seek to redeploy their capital.
</P>
<P>
Overbuilding in the country's cities was less of an issue than
it had been in the past, because stricter controls were helping to
manage the growth, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Most office markets around the country should remain strong in
1999, although slower projected economic growth will ease pressure
on already low vacancy rates, resulting in slower rental growth
and reduced demand for new construction.
</P>
<P>
The lodging industry is expected to again generate record
profits in 1998 with another strong year expected in 1999, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
It also predicted that institutional investors, including
pensions funds, would step up direct investments in shopping
centers during the coming year. But malls must constantly change
to continue attracting shoppers, as consumers nowadays have more
stores to choose from and Internet shopping will provide direct
competition to malls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
