<HEADLINE> Residential Housing Glut In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital has built
more residential housing than it needs and 88.5 percent of its
vacant buildings are residential housing, China Business News
reports, based on a recent study of 96 real estate development
companies by the Beijing Municipal Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The 96 companies account for 17 percent of Beijing's real
estate companies. They had 801,000 sq.m. of housing space vacant
by the end of August, which is 36.9 percent of the city's total
area in unsold commercial space.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that the companies had 5,518 apartments that
had remained unoccupied for at least a year and 2,644 apartments
that were still unsold after more than two years.
</P>
<P>
The state sector has the highest rate of unsold housing, with
72 percent of the housing of state-owned real estate companies
still waiting for buyers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
