<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South-South Countries Urged to Cooperate With G7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The South-South countries need
to cooperate with the Group of Seven (G7) industrialized countries
to boost the development of their economic and banking sectors, an
ESCAP official said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Group of 77's high-level conference on regional
and sub-regional cooperation under the South-South framework in
Nusa Dua, Bali Province, on Wednesday, Executive Secretary
Adrianus Mooy of the Economic and Social Commission for Asia and
the Pacific (ESCAP) said the cooperation is imperative to global
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Thus, there would be economic cooperation oriented to the
development of balanced and competitive global economies and the
socioeconomic disparities between the developed countries of the
North and the developing nations of the South could be reduced, he
was quoted by Antara News Agency Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation is also an effective means of encouraging and
developing the economic and banking sectors in each of the
South-South countries, Mooy, former governor of Bank Indonesia,
said.
</P>
<P>
To overcome the monetary crisis still affecting some Asian
countries including Indonesia, he underscored the need for these
countries to intensify the control of the banking sector and adopt
transparent banking rules.
</P>
<P>
To that end, he said, there must be good working mechanism
between the North and South at regional, sub-regional and national
levels.
</P>
<P>
The four-day high-level conference was opened on Wednesday by
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas, aiming to draw up a
recommendation for the South-South summit to be held in Havana in
2000.
</P>
<P>
The conference is being attended by ministers and ranking
officials from 132 countries, representatives of international
organizations and observers from Canada, Japan and South Korea. A
delegation from China is also attending the meeting at the
invitation of the organizers.
</P>
<P>
The Group of 77 was founded on June 15, 1964, after 77
countries signed a joint declaration in Geneva. 
</P>
</TEXT>
