<HEADLINE> Cuba, US to Renegotiate Immigration Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Cuban and U.S. officials will
hold a new round of talks on Friday to monitor compliance with
immigration agreements between the two countries, the Cuban
Foreign Ministry said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cuba and the United States signed their first immigration pact
in 1984, but the accords were soon suspended by Havana due to the
start of broadcasts from the anti-Castro Radio Marti, funded by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Relations returned to some degree of normalcy in May 1995 after
the signing of an agreement under which the U.S. pledged to grant
a minimum 20,000 visas to Cuban immigrants and to return illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has so far reportedly complied with its pledge,
granting 66,000 visas to Cuba and returning 1,373 illegal migrants.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Foreign Ministry spokesman Alejandro Gonzalez said the
Cuban delegation to Friday's talks will be headed by parliament
leader Ricardo Alarcon while the U.S. delegation will be led by
Under-Secretary for Latin American affairs John Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
Cuba and the U.S. do not have diplomatic ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
