<HEADLINE> New Rules on Moving in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Money is the main thing being
used to compensate Beijing's urban residents who have to move
because their houses are being demolished, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
This is stipulated in the Chinese capital's Managerial Measures
on the Removing of Urban Housing and the moving of Involved
Residents, which was officially adopted on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Beijing officially abolished its Detailed
Rules for the Implementation of Managerial Regulations on the
Removing of Urban Housing and the Moving of Urban Housing and the
moving of Involved Residents established by the State Council in
1991.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations will be the only basis for the Beijing
municipal government's work on this issue.
</P>
<P>
Besides money, Beijingers can also seek housing as
compensation. The new regulations' 27th item states that
residents can choose money or housing as compensation for their
demolished residences after discussions with parties responsible
for the removing and moving project.
</P>
<P>
A local housing official said that the measures do not limit
compensation to money because the city wants to ensure freedom of
choice.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, some residents can not find suitable hosing
immediately," he said. "We cannot leave them on the streets."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Luxembourg Faces Fine for Employment Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
here Wednesday that it has decided to seek financial penalties
against Luxembourg for violating the European Union's social law.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the EU's executive body, said Luxembourg has
failed to comply with a previous European Court judgement
concerning Luxembourg nationality requirement for the access to
employment in certain parts of the public sector.
</P>
<P>
The commission proposed that the European Court fix a fine of
14,000 European currency units (equivalent to about 11,966
U.S. dollars) for each day of non-compliance with the second
judgement of the court under an EU treaty.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg was judged by the court in 1996 as violating Article
48 of the treaty for reserving jobs in certain parts of the public
sector for its own nationals.
</P>
<P>
However, although almost two years have passed, the EU said,
Luxembourg has not adopted necessary measures to comply with the
judgement and allow European citizens access to the public service.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the commission has sought the European
Court's imposition of a daily fine on a member state in the social
area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Producing Recombinant Human Insulin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- China has become the third
country in the world to produce recombinant human insulin.
</P>
<P>
The product was developed by Dr. Gan Zhongru using new
bio-engineering technology, which is different from that used by
the U.S. Eli Lilly and Denmark's Novo Nordisk.
</P>
<P>
The product meets or even exceeds standards of similar imported
products in purity and ability to reduce blood sugar, according to
Beijing Union Medical College Hospital and three other hospitals
which used it to treat 100 diabetes patients from October 1997 to
April 1998.
</P>
<P>
China applied for an international patent for the product in
March and began to produce it in November.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Gan's partner, China Tonghua Dongbao Pharmaceutical
Co. Ltd. has spent 100 million yuan (about 12.5 million
U.S. dollars) on advanced production and testing facilities from
the U.S., Germany, Britain, and France.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 30 million diabetes sufferers, several
million of whom need insulin on a regular basis. In the past few
years, most of these people have depended on bovine insulin and
imported human insulin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
