<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3,000-Year-Old Carriages Found in Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered two large chariot pits in Shandong province, east
China, with two beautifully decorated imperial carriages, and
nearly 1,000 pieces of bronzeware, bone, and jade.
</P>
<P>
The two pits are located in the village of Qianzhangda in the
southern part of the province. The archeologists discovered them
during other excavation work. They say that the two carriages are
at least 3,000 years old and are still intact. They are 3.2 meters
long and 3.1 meters wide and have a painted awning decorated in
gold leaf.
</P>
<P>
In front of the carriages they found the remains of
horses. Archeologists said the horses were powerful and were
beautifully decorated before being buried as funerary objects.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists believe that decorated carriages indicate
imperial family members or members of the nobility.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Ethnic Group Series: Shamans: Living History in Miao Ethnic Group (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The doctor says that because of science and technology few
villagers still believe that shamans can cure diseases. In the
past, when a doctor wanted to give people inoculations, no one
would allow it even if it was free. But now, villagers will stand
in a long queue early in the morning when they see a notice to get
shots.
</P>
<P>
Tang Renzhong, an agronomist in the village of Xingbing,
Rongshui County, says that villagers used to burn incense and ask
shamans to chant incantations to drive away evil spirits that
could destroy crops, but they still lived in poverty.
</P>
<P>
But, hybrid rice is popular here now. In 1995, this poor county
became self-sufficient in grain for the first time. Rice output
doubled with the use of hybrid rice, Tang explains.
</P>
<P>
He says that villagers have had good harvests for several years
running, because of the use of the rice seeds, and chemical
fertilizers and pesticides. Per capita annual income in the
village was 1,000 yuan last year, and villagers no longer worry
about where their food and clothing are coming from.
</P>
<P>
With these changes, shamans have found it hard to find
successors. Jia Anhe says that his father, a former shaman,
stopped when his relatives died of illness even after shamans
prayed for them, and that his father told him not to live this way.
</P>
<P>
Jia, who is now the deputy director of the Agriculture Bureau
of Rongshui County, is busy every day promoting the use of hybrid
rice and agronomy in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
Jia's daughter is a primary school pupil. Jia says that he
hopes his daughter will become the first university student of his
family of shamans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Editor's Note: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The following is the third of a series of articles on the
fast-changing life and culture of the Zhuang, Miao, Yao, Shui, and
7 other ethnic groups in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region in
southern China. They are being prepared by Xinhua reporters to
mark the 40th anniversary of Guangxi on December 11.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi Ethnic Group Series:
</P>
<P>
Shamans: Living History in Miao Ethnic Group (1)
</P>
<P>
NANNING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Miao is one of the largest
ethnic groups in China, with more than 7 million people. They have
a tradition of worshiping gods and spirits, and in the past, a
professional or semi-professional shaman could be found in almost
every village.
</P>
<P>
The people believed that shamans were a link between the common
folk and the gods, between the present world and the next, and
they were asked to help people by praying for fortune and for
agricultural blessings and for good health.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years ago, Jia Weifu in Yubu village, Rongshui Miao
Autonomous county, was the most celebrated person in the
village. As a shaman, he treated sick people with straw ash and a
mysterious dance that was used for good harvests. These, together
with his incantations, meant that he could communicate with gods
and the spirit world.
</P>
<P>
Jia now raises cattle and pigs and crops. Tang Shaohui, the
village doctor, says, "I used to go to Jia for treatment when I
was ill, but now he comes to me when he's sick."
</P>
<P>
The more modern China became, the more shamans disappeared,
especially in developed cities and suburbs. Today they can only be
found in some remote villages. With the gradual decrease in the
number of shamans, came an increase in the number of doctors,
teachers and agronomists, even in the most remote villages.
</P>
<P>
The Miao in Guangxi live in compact communities. Jia lives in
the Damiao mountains. Jia's wife says that it's been a long time
since he was asked to chant incantations to drive away evil
spirits and treat people's illnesses. The family is also no longer
living in poverty and makes a better living by farming and selling
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
There's a motorcycle parked in front of Jia's wooden house, and
in the sun-lit lounge there's a television. On the wall, a
horizontal plaque says: Achieve Prosperity through Hard
Work. There are few reminders of the spirit world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
