<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Witnesses Rapid Growth of Telephone Subscriptions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Tibet -- the formerly information
inaccessible Roof of the World -- has witnessed a 20-fold increase
in the number of telephone subscribers over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Tibet Post and Telecommunications Bureau
show that in the regional capital of Lhasa 32 people out of every
100 are now telephone subscribers, and that nearly three people
out of 100 are telephone subscribers on average throughout the
region.
</P>
<P>
Today, all seven cities and prefectures in the region have
mobile phone telecommunications networks, and Lhasa has a digital
program controlled mobile phone network.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said that all of the region's 73 counties have
ground communications satellite stations and program-controlled
telecommunications offices, and local residents are able to make
either domestic long distance calls or international long distance
calls.
</P>
<P>
However, statistics indicate that in 1978, only one person out
of 1,000 was a telephone subscriber, 63 percent of the cities and
prefectures were without telephone exchange networks, and long
distance telecommunications were confined to the telegraph line.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet to Achieve Good Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Tibet, the Roof of the World, is
expected to have a grain harvest this year of an estimated
850,000 tons, 7.3 percent more than last year.
</P>
<P>
An official with the autonomous region's agricultural and
animal husbandry bureau said the per capita net income of farmers
and herdsmen is expected to reach 1,150 yuan (about 130
U.S. dollars) this year, six percent more than last year.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the recent good harvests to increased
investment in agriculture by the central and local governments,
the spread of technology, and the adoption of special local
policies such as exemption from agricultural tax.
</P>
<P>
The central and local governments have offered 220 million yuan
(26 million dollars) since 1996 to disseminate science and
technology for crop growing, build irrigation networks, and
invigorate low-yield farmland.
</P>
<P>
So far, some 1,300 irrigation canals and 5,290 reservoirs of
various sizes have been built in the region.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that about 200,000 Tibetan farmers and
herdsmen receive technical training each year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
