<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province to Build More Railways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province,
which has led the country in port and highway construction, plans
to spend some six billion yuan to build three local railways over
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Provincial government sources said this project will further
improve Shandong's communications network system and alleviate the
pressure on local cargo transportation, adding that the funds will
be raised through various channels at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Shandong, a major grain and energy producer, has built a series
of sea ports, but some of them have had to operate under capacity
due to the shortage of railways.
</P>
<P>
The new railways are designed to link a number of major cities
in Shandong, including Dezhou, Yantai and Yanzhou, to some
national railway trunks, such as the Beijing-Kowloon line and
the Beijing-Shanghai line.
</P>
<P>
The longest of the three, costing five billion yuan, will
extend 500 kilometers between Yantai, a major port city, and
Dezhou, a stop on the Beijing-Shanghai rail line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
