<HEADLINE> French-Speaking World Permanent Council Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Permanent Council of the
French-speaking world Wednesday opened its 31st Session in
Bucharest under the leadership of Boutros Boutros-Ghali, Secretary
General of the international organization.
</P>
<P>
The session preceded the 12th Ministerial Conference that will
take place in Bucharest on December 4 and 5, with the
participation of the personal representatives of heads of state or
government in the member states of the French-speaking world.
</P>
<P>
It is the first opportunity for Romania to host such a
gathering since it received full membership of the Movement in
Mauritius in 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to Boutros-Boutros Ghali, the two sessions will
debate "the main economic and technical policies" of this
international organization. He also said the gatherings would
"prepare" the conference of the economic and finance ministers due
to take place in Monaco, in April 14-15, 1999, and the 8th Summit
of the French-speaking world, due to be held in Moncton, Canada,
in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
The reform of the French-speaking world Agency will be approved
in order to make the international organization "become more
pragmatic, more flexible and more effective in the way it
operates", said Andrei Magheru, executive secretary of the
National Advisory Council for the French-speaking world at the
Ministerial Conference in Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
There were many specific issues that would be discussed, issues
of the academic cooperation in the field of media, the cultural,
economic cooperation, the issue of "information highways the
French-speaking world is concerned with, meaning that the Internet
should deliver information not only in English but also in
French", Andrei Magheru added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
