<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Proposes Monitoring Function in U.N. Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Wednesday proposed a new monitoring function in the
U.N. Special Mission to Afghanistan (UNSMA).
</P>
<P>
In his annual report on Afghanistan to the General Assembly and
the Security Council, Annan said reports of mass killings and
other forms of gross violations of human rights and international
humanitarian law in the country have become a major source of
concern to the international community at large and to the United
Nations in particular.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the primary objective of promoting respect for
minimum humanitarian standards and deterring massive and
systematic violations of human rights in the future, Annan
proposed to establish a separate civil affair unit in the UNSMA,
initially composed of 12 monitors who, security conditions
premitting, would be deployed in major centers in the country.
</P>
<P>
Annan said their exact location, mandate and functioning would
be determined following the return of an assessment team, which he
intended to dispatch to the country at an early date, with the
agreement of the Afghan authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
