<HEADLINE> U.S. Rejects Israel's Conditions for Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States dismissed
Wednesday Israel's conditions for a withdrawal from the West Bank
and demanded that the Wye accord with the Palestinians "should be
implemented as signed."
</P>
<P>
In a statement, State Department spokesman James Rubin said the
withdrawal is an obligation. "We do not think it is appropriate to
add new conditions."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also condemned an attack on an Israeli soldier in
Ramallah, an Arab town on the West Bank, which he said "is clearly
the kind of violence that has no place in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
In Jerusalem, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
office said Wednesday that troop pullbacks would be delayed unless
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat stopped saying he would establish
a Palestinian state next May.
</P>
<P>
Israel also insists that incitement of rioters be halted and
that Israel alone decide which Palestinian prisoners to free under
October's Wye accord signed in rural Maryland.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. rejection of the Israeli conditions puts the
administration on a collision course with Israel little more than
a week before a scheduled trip there by President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. position was that neither side should say things that
appear provocative or are designed to prejudge the outcome of
negotiations still to be held.
</P>
<P>
American mediator Dennis Ross and his deputy, Aaron Miller,
will go to the region in a few days to try and ease the conflict
in advance of Clinton's trip, a senior U.S. official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
