<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. General Assembly Calls for Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The 53rd General
Assembly on Wednesday adopted six resolutions on the question of
Palestine and two on the situation of Middle East, calling for
self-determination for the Palestinian people and demanding the
Israeli withdrawal from the Golden Heights captured from Syria in
the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
The resolutions on the two issues, debated separately every
year by the General Assembly, were again endorsed by overwhelming
majority this year.
</P>
<P>
The United States jointed Israel by casting the only negative
votes against five of the resolutions, while abstaining on the one
about Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
A resolution on the peaceful settlement of the question of
Palestine was adopted by a vote of 154 to two, with three
abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The resolution stressed "the realization of the rights of the
Palestinian people, primarily the right to self-determination," and
"the withdrawal of Israel from the Palestinian territory occupied
since 1967."
</P>
<P>
The resolution also "stresses the necessity for commitment to
the principle of land for peace and the implementation of Security
Council resolutions 242 (1967) and 338 (1973), which form the
basis of the Middle East peace process, and the need for the
immediate and scrupulous implementation of the agreements reached
between parties."
</P>
<P>
The resolution urged U.N. members to expedite economic and
technical assistance to the Palestinian people and emphasised the
importance for the United Nations to play a more active and
expanded role in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
By a vote of 149 to one with seven abstentions, the General
Assembly said in a resolution that a 1948 decision by Israel to
impose its laws and jurisdiction on all parts of Jerusalem,
including the eastern part captured in 1967, was illegal, null
and void. Israel voted against the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The resolution deplored the transfer by some countries of
their diplomatic missions to Jerusalem, which Israel regards as
its undivided capital.
</P>
<P>
Another resolution, adopted by 97 votes to two with 58
abstentions, called upon Israel to resume peace talks on the
Syrian and Lebanese tracks and to respect undertakings reached in
previous rounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
