<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Agriculture Secretary Acquitted by Jury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. jury on Wednesday
acquitted former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy of 30 corruption
charges.
</P>
<P>
The verdict ended an investigation by independent counsel
Donald Smaltz, who spent nearly 20 million dollar and four years
investigating allegations Espy accepted free sports tickets,
travel and other favors from companies he regulated.
</P>
<P>
Espy, a former Democratic member of Congress from Mississippi,
and the nation's first African-American agriculture secretary,
resigned from the Clinton cabinet in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The verdict from the predominantly black jury came after a
lengthy probe by one of the first independent counsels named to
investigate members of the Clinton administration. Other
high-ranking Clinton aides -- including current and former cabinet
members Alexis Herman, Bruce Babbitt, Henry Cisneros, and Ron
Brown -- were also targets of separate probes.
</P>
<P>
During the trial, the prosecution called 70 witnesses while the
defense did not present any testimony. The jury rejected the
prosecution's case, ruling that Espy was guilty of nothing more
than accepting gifts and social courtesies from friends, and did
not alter Agriculture Department policy because of the favors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
