<HEADLINE> Smoking More Dangerous for Women, UK Study Reveals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Smoking is more likely to kill
women than men, according to the largest ever British study of
lung cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
The study, presented at the British Thoracic Society Winter
Meeting in London on Wednesday, revealed that women are more
vulnerable to the most fatal type of lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
The research, carried out by the Royal College of Physicians
Research Unit, involved 1,600 cancer patients in 46 hospitals in
the UK.
</P>
<P>
It showed that women who smoke are twice as likely as men to
develop small cell lung cancer, an insidious form of the disease
which spreads more rapidly than other forms. Seven out of 10 of
these cases could not be helped by surgery.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said that changing patterns of smoking
behavior, as many British women took up the habit a decade after
men who smoked heavily during the Second World War, may be one of
the reasons that women have less resistance to small cell lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
Women may also smoke in a different way to men, researchers
explained, like taking shorter, sharper inhalations, which could
have an effect on the kind and severity of cancer that they
develop.
</P>
<P>
Researchers hope the findings will give more impetus to drives
to cut the increasing number of teenage girls in the UK taking up
smoking, which accounts for a huge percentage of lung cancer
cases.
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, only one in five 15-year old girls in Britain
smoked. Now the number has climbed to one in three.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
