<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Group Asks UN to Investigate U.S. Bombing in Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The 22 Arab states at
the United Nations on Wednesday once again asked the U.N. Security
Council to approve an investigation of the U.S. bombing on a
factory in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Group sent a revised draft resolution to the President
of the Security Council, requesting U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan dispatch a mission to verify all facts concerning the
Al-Shifa factory, including its production and ownership.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution also asked Annan to submit a report on
the mission's findings within one month of the reslution's adoption.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and the Arab Group requested a U.N. investigation
immediately after the attack and demanded compensation from the
United States for the cost of the plant.
</P>
<P>
The United States considers Sudan a sponsor of terrorism. It
bombed the Khartoum factory and a site in Afghanistan after its
embassies in Tanzania and Kenya were attacked on August 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0356 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Stocks Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. stocks fell Wednesday on
discouraging news from two blue-chip index components about their
business performance.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average, covering the trend of 30 big
companies, closed 69 points lower at 9,064.54 and broader market
indicators fell modestly, based on preliminary data.
</P>
<P>
Aircraft maker Boeing, a Dow component, announced that it will
cut 20,000 jobs over the next two years due to lower demand from
Asia where the financial crisis originated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, retailer Sears, another Dow member, said that its
sales retreated last month and its earnings for the year would
only rise marginally despite a shopping season is ahead.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts attributed the market decline to continuing
profit taking following weeks of gains in major indexes but others
said it may reflect investors' uncertainty about U.S. and world
economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
The market followed Tuesday's pattern of low opening with the
Dow down 178 points at one point Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq fell 8.55 to 1,995.20 and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 4.03 to 1,171.25.
</P>
<P>
On the New York Stock Exchange, decliners led advancers 9-7
with trading volume down to 724 million shares from 781 million
previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
