<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares End Down for 3rd Session in Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Profit warnings and poor start
on Wall Street dragged European shares down Wednesday for the
third session in a row.
</P>
<P>
The UK's FTSE 100 index closed 30.3 points or 0.6 percent lower
at 5,507.2.
</P>
<P>
While the decline was poor, investors were glad to see the
market hold up slightly against the drag of a 100-plus fall on the
Dow Jones Industrial Average.
</P>
<P>
Germany's benchmark Xetra Dax index fell deeper into negative
territory. By 1530 GMT it was down 1.8 percent at 4,690.62 points
as profit-taking continued.
</P>
<P>
"We're going down with the U.S. market as our market lacks
impulse," one trader in Frankfurt said.
</P>
<P>
The slump on Wall Street dragged down by Boeing Co's gloomy
financial forecast also weighed on French investors.
</P>
<P>
The Cac 40 index closed down 38.43 points at 3,649.91. "We're
following New York, which is very weak because of the bad news
from Boeing," said one Paris dealer.
</P>
<P>
Swiss shares closed some 0.5 percent lower after initial gains
were erased by a crumbling dollar and the weaker start on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
Dutch shares closed just over 2 percent down despite a higher
start, with only a few buyers around in morning trade and
sentiment soon turned bearish when investors started to sell large
amounts of shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Tory Leader in Upper House Sacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition
Conservative Party leader William Hague sacked his leader in the
House of Lords Wednesday, plunging the Tory party into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Conservative peers were in open revolt after Lord Cranborne was
booted out by Hague for agreeing to a government plan to save
seats for almost 100 hereditary Lords. Lord Strathclyde was later
appointed as his replacement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was part of a compromise to win an easy passage
in the upper House for the government's plans for constitutional
reform, including the abolition of voting rights for all
hereditaries.
</P>
<P>
It had been kept secret and was only revealed by Hague during a
dramatic Question Time clash Wednesday. He insisted his party had
rejected the deal and accused the government of a "huge climbdown"
which showed that the prime minister had no principles on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
But Prime Minister Tony Blair hit back, claiming the deal had
been done with Lord Cranborne, proving Hague was not in control of
his own party.
</P>
<P>
Speaking shortly afterwards, Lord Cranborne admitted he had
"behaved quite outrageously."
</P>
<P>
He said he had "exceeded his authority and gone behind his
leader's back."
</P>
<P>
But he added, "In any conflict between loyalty to the party and
loyalty to this House, my judgement must be about what I think is
best for the future of this House."
</P>
<P>
Hague, in a letter to the sacked peer, declared, "As you know,
at our meeting this afternoon I explained that following the
events today I had no option but to require you to step down from
your position as leader of the Conservative Party in the House of
Lords.
</P>
<P>
"It can never be acceptable for a member of the front bench to
seek to bring about a change in the policy of the party without
the knowledge or agreement of the party leader or the shadow
cabinet."
</P>
<P>
The government is committed to abolishing the rights of all 750
hereditary peers to sit and vote in the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
The plan has been opposed by the Tories and the government
fears they could use their inbuilt majority in the upper House to
block the proposal and throw its parliamentary program into
disarray with guerrilla warfare over the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981203.0361 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
